1
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:15,400
The men who live with the queens,

2
00:00:15,466 --> 00:00:17,733
we're here with Ko Woo-rim and Kangnam.

3
00:00:17,800 --> 00:00:21,933
Sang-hwa and Kangnam have been married
for eight years already.

4
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:22,933
-Yes.
-What's it like?

5
00:00:23,000 --> 00:00:24,800
Has anything changed
since the newlywed days?

6
00:00:24,866 --> 00:00:26,833
Back when we were dating,

7
00:00:26,900 --> 00:00:28,433
I didn't think she would be

8
00:00:28,500 --> 00:00:29,900
this scary.

9
00:00:31,266 --> 00:00:32,566
Is he allowed to say this?

10
00:00:32,633 --> 00:00:34,833
-I see.
-She had a way

11
00:00:34,900 --> 00:00:37,500
of keeping me under discipline
even when we were dating.

12
00:00:37,566 --> 00:00:40,400
She was like that
even before we got married.

13
00:00:40,466 --> 00:00:41,533
After we married,

14
00:00:41,600 --> 00:00:43,733
I didn't expect her
to discipline me this much.

15
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:44,866
DISCIPLINE BEYOND EXPECTATION

16
00:00:44,933 --> 00:00:46,733
I didn't think it'd be this serious.

17
00:00:46,800 --> 00:00:48,033
You're under total discipline.

18
00:00:48,100 --> 00:00:51,300
-You're tied up.
-But that's why I've been doing well.

19
00:00:51,366 --> 00:00:53,100
I'm grateful for her.

20
00:00:53,166 --> 00:00:54,933
But it's unlike anything you can imagine.

21
00:00:55,000 --> 00:00:56,800
My life is

22
00:00:56,866 --> 00:00:57,833
very intense.

23
00:00:59,633 --> 00:01:00,700
He has no filter.

24
00:01:00,900 --> 00:01:02,500
HOW WILL HE DEAL WITH HER LATER?

25
00:01:02,566 --> 00:01:05,099
Is it difficult because
you have to adjust yourself to her?

26
00:01:05,166 --> 00:01:06,733
I can't fully adjust to her.

27
00:01:06,800 --> 00:01:08,600
Her lifestyle is way too strict.

28
00:01:08,666 --> 00:01:11,366
But I wanted to at least meet her halfway.

29
00:01:11,433 --> 00:01:13,533
And that life is already so intense.

30
00:01:14,766 --> 00:01:17,066
But Sang-hwa
can't help but show her scary side

31
00:01:17,133 --> 00:01:18,633
because you keep making her angry.

32
00:01:18,700 --> 00:01:22,933
You have a popular series called
Lee Sang-hwa's Red Light, Green Light.

33
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:25,533
I bet no YouTubers
risk their lives for content like I do.

34
00:01:25,600 --> 00:01:27,000
-But why?
-He's something.

35
00:01:27,066 --> 00:01:31,100
She didn't really like how I ate
because I'd eat too much.

36
00:01:31,166 --> 00:01:32,500
I had eight meals a day.

37
00:01:32,566 --> 00:01:34,000
-Eight?
-She told me to stop,

38
00:01:34,066 --> 00:01:35,733
especially in the middle of the night.

39
00:01:35,800 --> 00:01:38,666
That was when I got the idea
for that new content.

40
00:01:38,733 --> 00:01:40,966
What would happen if I made <i>ramyeon</i>

41
00:01:41,033 --> 00:01:43,333
and ate it while she was sound asleep?

42
00:01:43,400 --> 00:01:46,500
So with immense nervousness,
I tried making it.

43
00:01:46,566 --> 00:01:51,233
That person is sleeping upstairs.

44
00:01:51,300 --> 00:01:55,400
RISKING LIFE LATE IN THE NIGHT TO PLAY
LEE SANG-HWA'S RED LIGHT, GREEN LIGHT

45
00:01:55,466 --> 00:01:56,566
I'LL ENJOY THE RAMYEON

46
00:01:56,633 --> 00:01:58,900
-It was 3 a.m.
-3 a.m.?

47
00:01:58,966 --> 00:02:00,233
He's really something.

48
00:02:01,466 --> 00:02:02,366
NERVOUS…

49
00:02:02,433 --> 00:02:03,866
Look at his face.

50
00:02:04,966 --> 00:02:07,166
I was already scared out of my mind.

51
00:02:08,133 --> 00:02:09,133
Oppa!

52
00:02:10,400 --> 00:02:12,266
-"Oppa!" Here she comes.
-I can see her feet.

53
00:02:12,333 --> 00:02:14,100
The scariest feet in this world!

54
00:02:14,166 --> 00:02:15,233
"THAT PERSON" IS HERE

55
00:02:15,300 --> 00:02:16,900
Why do you do this, seriously?

56
00:02:17,166 --> 00:02:18,300
OH, WHATEVER

57
00:02:18,366 --> 00:02:19,200
ARE YOU CRAZY?

58
00:02:19,266 --> 00:02:20,133
He goes for it!

59
00:02:20,200 --> 00:02:22,133
SWIFTLY STOPS HIM!

60
00:02:22,400 --> 00:02:23,233
RETRY

61
00:02:23,300 --> 00:02:25,200
<i>Those noodles were burning hot.</i>

62
00:02:25,266 --> 00:02:26,966
She grabbed it with her hand.

63
00:02:27,233 --> 00:02:28,233
USED HER BARE HAND

64
00:02:28,300 --> 00:02:29,700
Those noodles were burning hot.

65
00:02:29,766 --> 00:02:31,133
She just took them away.

66
00:02:31,766 --> 00:02:33,366
That was around 2 a.m.

67
00:02:33,433 --> 00:02:34,333
-Fondue.
-It's fondue.

68
00:02:34,400 --> 00:02:36,600
He's doing that at two in the morning.

69
00:02:36,666 --> 00:02:38,066
That's chocolate, right?

70
00:02:38,133 --> 00:02:39,333
And from upstairs…

71
00:02:39,400 --> 00:02:42,000
-The lights came on.
-The lights turned on!

72
00:02:43,133 --> 00:02:45,766
SLOWLY
SHE SHOWS HERSELF…

73
00:02:45,833 --> 00:02:48,166
-Kangnam doesn't know.
-I didn't know.

74
00:02:48,233 --> 00:02:49,666
MESMERIZED BY THE FONDUE…

75
00:02:50,066 --> 00:02:51,000
What are you doing?

76
00:02:51,066 --> 00:02:52,866
STARTLED

77
00:02:53,566 --> 00:02:55,100
GLANCES

78
00:02:55,666 --> 00:02:57,633
THE FINAL EFFORT

79
00:02:57,700 --> 00:02:58,766
<i>Stop that.</i>

80
00:02:59,500 --> 00:03:00,900
BUT HE DOESN'T GIVE UP

81
00:03:02,033 --> 00:03:03,933
AGAIN, SWIFTLY STOPS HIM

82
00:03:04,500 --> 00:03:06,200
-<i>Go and wash your hands.</i>
-My gosh.

83
00:03:06,266 --> 00:03:08,633
Even my hands trembled
when I filmed those.

84
00:03:08,700 --> 00:03:11,100
From the moment
she walked down the stairs,

85
00:03:11,166 --> 00:03:13,166
-my subscribers got scared.
-It's a horror movie.

86
00:03:13,233 --> 00:03:15,033
-They could see her feet.
-Yes, horror.

87
00:03:15,100 --> 00:03:17,400
Even my editors flinched like this.

88
00:03:17,466 --> 00:03:19,000
TREMBLING WHILE EDITING

89
00:03:19,066 --> 00:03:22,300
Wouldn't Sang-hwa become furious
if I painted her car another color?

90
00:03:22,366 --> 00:03:24,966
I'm going to paint it pink.

91
00:03:25,033 --> 00:03:27,033
-This was shocking.
-That was insane.

92
00:03:27,100 --> 00:03:29,433
I got a good scolding after this one.

93
00:03:29,500 --> 00:03:30,500
PLEASE DON'T DO IT

94
00:03:30,566 --> 00:03:31,766
HE REALLY DID IT

95
00:03:31,833 --> 00:03:32,800
What's he doing?

96
00:03:32,866 --> 00:03:35,100
-That's not even a car wrap.
-What are you doing?

97
00:03:35,166 --> 00:03:36,100
FROM DULL BLACK

98
00:03:36,166 --> 00:03:37,300
TO PRINCESS PINK

99
00:03:37,600 --> 00:03:39,100
THE PINK CAR SHOWS UP WITH A BOW

100
00:03:39,166 --> 00:03:40,466
<i>It wasn't wrapping, but paint.</i>

101
00:03:40,533 --> 00:03:41,666
<i>Isn't that my car?</i>

102
00:03:42,400 --> 00:03:43,566
<i>She's furious.</i>

103
00:03:43,633 --> 00:03:44,800
This is the worst.

104
00:03:44,866 --> 00:03:45,866
Get out now.

105
00:03:46,666 --> 00:03:48,333
She must've been actually furious.

106
00:03:48,900 --> 00:03:51,366
<i>I really hate it. I hate it.</i>

107
00:03:51,433 --> 00:03:54,033
I'M IN TROUBLE

108
00:03:54,100 --> 00:03:55,500
It's a wonder that he's still alive.

109
00:03:56,633 --> 00:03:57,833
That was very dangerous.

110
00:03:57,900 --> 00:03:59,466
I got a good scolding for that,

111
00:03:59,533 --> 00:04:00,766
even from her parents.

112
00:04:00,833 --> 00:04:02,133
HE PAID FOR THE TROUBLE…

113
00:04:02,200 --> 00:04:05,666
But I got over three million views
for that video alone.

114
00:04:05,733 --> 00:04:07,800
-Did you get the car restored?
-That was

115
00:04:07,866 --> 00:04:10,133
-peel-off paint.
-I see.

116
00:04:10,200 --> 00:04:11,433
-Yes.
-What a relief.

117
00:04:11,500 --> 00:04:12,400
You can peel it off.

118
00:04:12,466 --> 00:04:14,066
Gosh, I'm so glad.

119
00:04:15,166 --> 00:04:17,733
But even now, we often see some residue.

120
00:04:17,800 --> 00:04:19,033
I'm sure.

121
00:04:19,100 --> 00:04:20,733
Then I get scolded for another two hours.

122
00:04:20,800 --> 00:04:22,400
"Why did you do this?
We're still seeing the paint."

123
00:04:22,466 --> 00:04:24,100
STILL PAYING FOR IT…

124
00:04:24,166 --> 00:04:26,066
After Woo-rim watched the video, he said,

125
00:04:26,133 --> 00:04:29,266
-"It's a wonder that he's still alive."
-Yes.

126
00:04:29,333 --> 00:04:30,633
You must be in shock.

127
00:04:30,700 --> 00:04:33,833
-That's just unimaginable.
-No.

128
00:04:33,900 --> 00:04:37,533
I think Sang-hwa is a big-hearted person.

129
00:04:37,600 --> 00:04:40,666
When he pulls a prank, she gets angry
and stops him at that moment,

130
00:04:40,733 --> 00:04:43,066
but when that moment ends,

131
00:04:43,133 --> 00:04:44,433
she switches right back.

132
00:04:44,500 --> 00:04:46,566
She also enjoyed that video

133
00:04:46,633 --> 00:04:48,300
after it was all edited.

134
00:04:48,366 --> 00:04:50,200
-She's a chill person.
-Woo-rim.

135
00:04:50,266 --> 00:04:53,266
What if you painted
Yuna's car pink like that?

136
00:04:53,333 --> 00:04:56,166
I have a feeling she wouldn't talk to me
for at least three days.

137
00:04:57,433 --> 00:05:00,633
She'll do a triple spin
and slap him across the face.

138
00:05:00,700 --> 00:05:01,933
As she spins.

139
00:05:02,300 --> 00:05:03,666
TRIPLE SLAP

140
00:05:03,733 --> 00:05:05,566
That could easily rake in
20 million views.

141
00:05:05,633 --> 00:05:07,133
-That's…
-He only cares about views.

142
00:05:07,200 --> 00:05:09,266
That's easily 20 million!
You have to do it!

143
00:05:09,333 --> 00:05:10,500
It's not about the views.

144
00:05:10,566 --> 00:05:12,766
You'll lose days off your remaining life.

145
00:05:12,833 --> 00:05:14,800
-I keep losing my days.
-You'll lose your life.

146
00:05:14,866 --> 00:05:16,733
-Has she not talked for three days?
-Three?

147
00:05:17,300 --> 00:05:18,500
-No, not yet.
-Surely not.

148
00:05:18,566 --> 00:05:19,633
But you do fight, right?

149
00:05:19,700 --> 00:05:21,766
I don't think we ever fight.

150
00:05:21,833 --> 00:05:24,100
She got mad at you
when you played games all day.

151
00:05:24,166 --> 00:05:26,600
-See? There was something.
-Oh, right.

152
00:05:26,666 --> 00:05:28,500
He was trying to hide it!

153
00:05:28,566 --> 00:05:30,800
-Good one! You got him.
-Of course.

154
00:05:30,866 --> 00:05:31,866
Do you know why I'm here?

155
00:05:31,933 --> 00:05:33,833
-To talk about you!
-It's not just him.

156
00:05:34,133 --> 00:05:35,966
THE HONORARY TRUTH SPILLER, KANGNAM

157
00:05:36,033 --> 00:05:37,466
What happened exactly?

158
00:05:37,533 --> 00:05:40,633
-She got really mad at you. Tell them.
-Well, it was…

159
00:05:40,700 --> 00:05:41,700
You played all day, huh?

160
00:05:41,766 --> 00:05:42,933
It technically wasn't a fight.

161
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:44,400
-I got scolded.
-She scolded you.

162
00:05:44,466 --> 00:05:47,433
I've been actively working lately,

163
00:05:47,500 --> 00:05:49,900
spending most of my time out of the house.

164
00:05:49,966 --> 00:05:51,433
<i>So when I'm home,</i>

165
00:05:51,500 --> 00:05:54,400
<i>-she wants to spend some time together.</i>
<i>-Of course.</i>

166
00:05:54,466 --> 00:05:58,333
On that day, I was being foolish

167
00:05:58,400 --> 00:06:00,133
and wanted to enjoy my own time.

168
00:06:00,200 --> 00:06:02,066
-You were tired from working too.
-Yes.

169
00:06:02,133 --> 00:06:03,833
So I played video games for a bit.

170
00:06:03,900 --> 00:06:05,733
I told her I'd play for an hour,

171
00:06:05,800 --> 00:06:07,266
which turned into two.

172
00:06:07,333 --> 00:06:08,566
Then she came in and asked,

173
00:06:08,633 --> 00:06:10,633
"How much longer will you play?"

174
00:06:10,700 --> 00:06:12,600
I said, "I'll be done soon."

175
00:06:12,666 --> 00:06:13,766
So she left the room.

176
00:06:13,833 --> 00:06:15,233
Then, another hour or two passed by.

177
00:06:15,300 --> 00:06:16,666
You continued to play.

178
00:06:16,733 --> 00:06:18,233
-That's too long.
-The thing is,

179
00:06:18,300 --> 00:06:20,000
she stopped checking on me
after a while.

180
00:06:20,066 --> 00:06:22,433
I realized that
I should probably wrap it up.

181
00:06:22,500 --> 00:06:24,633
So I turned it off and left the room.

182
00:06:24,700 --> 00:06:27,633
Usually, when I come out of the room,
she usually looks back at me.

183
00:06:27,700 --> 00:06:29,033
That day, she didn't.

184
00:06:29,100 --> 00:06:32,266
-How scary.
-The back of her head seemed so cold.

185
00:06:32,333 --> 00:06:33,866
I know that feeling.

186
00:06:33,933 --> 00:06:35,733
-So…
-You could see her anger from behind.

187
00:06:35,800 --> 00:06:36,733
I knew I was screwed.

188
00:06:36,800 --> 00:06:39,533
I had to do whatever I could
to regain her favor.

189
00:06:39,600 --> 00:06:40,633
You should kneel.

190
00:06:41,400 --> 00:06:42,966
I went straight to do the dishes.

191
00:06:43,033 --> 00:06:44,400
-Right.
-Suddenly?

192
00:06:44,466 --> 00:06:47,733
I suddenly went to do the dishes.
So that happened once.

193
00:06:48,466 --> 00:06:51,066
She noticed him doing the dishes,
found him cute,

194
00:06:51,133 --> 00:06:52,933
and just chuckled.

195
00:06:53,000 --> 00:06:55,666
You would've been in so much trouble
if you didn't do the dishes.

196
00:06:55,733 --> 00:06:57,366
That was a good one.

197
00:06:57,433 --> 00:06:59,100
The day he played video games too much.

198
00:06:59,166 --> 00:07:01,400
-I have lots of stories to tell.
-I'm sure you do.

199
00:07:01,466 --> 00:07:02,866
I'll spill them one by one.

200
00:07:02,933 --> 00:07:04,633
-That was funny.
-Tell us when you remember.

201
00:07:04,700 --> 00:07:08,300
Is there a reason why Sang-hwa
won't let you eat late at night?

202
00:07:08,366 --> 00:07:10,966
My weight fluctuated from 100 kg

203
00:07:11,033 --> 00:07:12,600
to 60 kg

204
00:07:12,666 --> 00:07:13,900
back to 90 kg and then 70 kg…

205
00:07:13,966 --> 00:07:15,833
It kept going up and down.

206
00:07:15,900 --> 00:07:17,533
We went to a health checkup

207
00:07:17,600 --> 00:07:20,300
and found that I had
a serious case of fatty liver

208
00:07:20,366 --> 00:07:22,466
that can be life-threatening.

209
00:07:22,533 --> 00:07:23,600
It alarmed Sang-hwa,

210
00:07:23,666 --> 00:07:27,766
so she began to cook from that day on,

211
00:07:27,833 --> 00:07:30,033
and built my workout plans too.

212
00:07:30,100 --> 00:07:33,733
Then, my numbers improved
in just five months

213
00:07:33,800 --> 00:07:36,333
without taking any medication.

214
00:07:36,566 --> 00:07:38,300
AMAZED

215
00:07:38,366 --> 00:07:40,833
I'm very grateful for her.

216
00:07:40,900 --> 00:07:43,300
-I think that's why…
-She's your guardian angel.

217
00:07:43,366 --> 00:07:46,166
…she tries even harder
to keep me disciplined.

218
00:07:46,833 --> 00:07:49,800
I wouldn't call that "discipline."

219
00:07:49,866 --> 00:07:51,400
-She takes care of me.
-Yes.

220
00:07:51,466 --> 00:07:52,966
She cried a lot, in the beginning.

221
00:07:53,033 --> 00:07:55,133
The doctor made it sound dire,

222
00:07:55,200 --> 00:07:57,733
like, "Your husband
is in critical condition."

223
00:07:57,800 --> 00:07:59,133
-I see.
-And so,

224
00:07:59,200 --> 00:08:01,900
from the next day,
she began to make me run.

225
00:08:01,966 --> 00:08:03,266
And I cried more than she did.

226
00:08:03,600 --> 00:08:04,600
REVENGE FOR HER TEARS

227
00:08:04,666 --> 00:08:06,500
-I almost died.
-That's just exhaustion.

228
00:08:06,566 --> 00:08:09,433
One day,
she suddenly dropped me off at Wangsimni.

229
00:08:09,500 --> 00:08:11,133
She suddenly dropped me off.

230
00:08:11,200 --> 00:08:13,700
-She told you to get out of the car?
-Yes, so I did.

231
00:08:13,766 --> 00:08:16,300
And she told me to run about 10 km
back to our home in Yongsan.

232
00:08:16,533 --> 00:08:17,900
STILL DUMBFOUNDED

233
00:08:18,500 --> 00:08:20,333
From Wangsimni? That's so far.

234
00:08:20,400 --> 00:08:22,333
-Did you two fight?
-It wasn't that.

235
00:08:22,400 --> 00:08:24,166
No, we were having a great day together.

236
00:08:24,233 --> 00:08:26,866
WE WERE HAVING A WONDERFUL TIME…

237
00:08:26,933 --> 00:08:27,800
All of a sudden, "Get out."

238
00:08:27,866 --> 00:08:29,900
I guess I still have my Japanese side.

239
00:08:29,966 --> 00:08:31,166
In Japanese, I said, "What?"

240
00:08:32,700 --> 00:08:33,799
RUN HOME FROM HERE?

241
00:08:33,866 --> 00:08:36,166
-You were that flustered.
-I really was!

242
00:08:36,233 --> 00:08:37,799
She went, "Get out," so I said, "Why?"

243
00:08:37,866 --> 00:08:39,366
She told me to run back to Yongsan.

244
00:08:39,433 --> 00:08:42,166
And she even took my phone
in case I called a cab.

245
00:08:42,233 --> 00:08:44,066
She's meticulous.

246
00:08:44,133 --> 00:08:45,633
I thought I was going to die.

247
00:08:45,700 --> 00:08:47,066
A tearful run back home.

248
00:08:47,133 --> 00:08:49,400
-So many tears.
-I thought, "Why did I become fat?"

249
00:08:49,466 --> 00:08:51,000
"Get out, oppa."

250
00:08:51,066 --> 00:08:53,100
Did you lose weight by running?

251
00:08:53,166 --> 00:08:55,066
I even had a herniated back disc,

252
00:08:55,133 --> 00:08:58,033
but I can do this now,
so it improved me overall.

253
00:08:58,300 --> 00:08:59,600
NODS

254
00:08:59,666 --> 00:09:01,466
It helped clear my brain too.

255
00:09:01,533 --> 00:09:04,366
Speaking of running,
we have an avid runner among us.

256
00:09:04,433 --> 00:09:06,233
-Stop joking.
-He runs marathons.

257
00:09:06,300 --> 00:09:08,800
-No way!
-He does it all the time.

258
00:09:08,866 --> 00:09:10,333
-You run marathons?
-He does.

259
00:09:10,400 --> 00:09:12,300
-The 4 km ones?
-No, proper ones.

260
00:09:12,366 --> 00:09:14,833
-I've run a half-marathon.
-That's about 20 km.

261
00:09:15,033 --> 00:09:15,866
AMAZED

262
00:09:15,933 --> 00:09:18,000
How long have you been running?
Several months?

263
00:09:18,066 --> 00:09:20,033
-About a year and a half.
-A year and a half?

264
00:09:20,100 --> 00:09:21,833
Yet you didn't see any change?

265
00:09:22,066 --> 00:09:23,966
WHAT EVERYONE WANTS TO KNOW

266
00:09:24,033 --> 00:09:25,566
Actually, I've been gaining weight.

267
00:09:25,633 --> 00:09:27,166
-What?
-Really?

268
00:09:27,233 --> 00:09:29,966
-It helps improve my appetite.
-Your appetite?

269
00:09:30,033 --> 00:09:32,000
-It happens.
-He works out to gain an appetite.

270
00:09:32,066 --> 00:09:34,566
That means you've been
eating more than before.

271
00:09:34,633 --> 00:09:36,600
I do eat more than I used to.

272
00:09:36,666 --> 00:09:39,000
He's still keeping his shape
because he works out.

273
00:09:39,066 --> 00:09:41,000
Otherwise, he'd be bigger.

274
00:09:41,066 --> 00:09:45,200
Sang-hwa isn't the only one
who looks after Kangnam.

275
00:09:45,266 --> 00:09:48,000
He got licensed as a sports masseuse

276
00:09:48,066 --> 00:09:50,666
-for Sang-hwa's sake.
-That's amazing.

277
00:09:50,733 --> 00:09:51,566
It was a while ago.

278
00:09:51,633 --> 00:09:54,766
As you probably know,
athletes are often in pain.

279
00:09:54,833 --> 00:09:57,633
Especially with Sang-hwa.
She overused her knees,

280
00:09:57,700 --> 00:09:59,200
so she falls like five times a day.

281
00:09:59,266 --> 00:10:01,133
-She does?
-It's that bad?

282
00:10:01,200 --> 00:10:04,166
She's also missing a tendon in her ankle.

283
00:10:04,233 --> 00:10:06,233
-Like no ligaments?
-Right.

284
00:10:06,300 --> 00:10:08,766
So she's always in pain
if I don't massage her.

285
00:10:08,833 --> 00:10:11,800
I thought I could give her
better massages once I got licensed.

286
00:10:11,866 --> 00:10:13,333
Do you do it often?

287
00:10:13,400 --> 00:10:15,433
-Almost every day.
-Every day?

288
00:10:15,500 --> 00:10:18,466
-Otherwise, she's in pain.
-I see.

289
00:10:18,533 --> 00:10:20,400
And she has a bad tech neck too.

290
00:10:20,466 --> 00:10:23,100
She always skated like this,
so the back of her neck sticks out.

291
00:10:23,166 --> 00:10:25,066
So she needs a massage.

292
00:10:25,133 --> 00:10:30,300
When my wife feels under the weather
or is in pain from time to time,

293
00:10:30,366 --> 00:10:33,433
I also massage her the best I can.

294
00:10:33,500 --> 00:10:34,666
They sacrificed their bodies

295
00:10:34,733 --> 00:10:37,333
<i>-to bring glory to our country.</i>
<i>-Exactly.</i>

296
00:10:37,400 --> 00:10:38,733
<i>-Yes.</i>
<i>-You're right.</i>

297
00:10:38,800 --> 00:10:40,766
Maybe this is a former athlete thing,

298
00:10:40,833 --> 00:10:43,000
but the pressure
I usually apply to most people

299
00:10:43,066 --> 00:10:44,233
isn't enough for her.

300
00:10:44,300 --> 00:10:45,533
-I see.
-What?

301
00:10:45,600 --> 00:10:48,166
-You must go really deep.
-All the way.

302
00:10:48,233 --> 00:10:49,666
"Ugh! Hngh!"

303
00:10:49,733 --> 00:10:51,433
-I…
-"Argh!" I need to do it like this.

304
00:10:51,500 --> 00:10:54,200
Only then will she be pleased.
You can never do it lightly.

305
00:10:54,266 --> 00:10:55,900
Yuna's also thin and dainty,

306
00:10:55,966 --> 00:10:57,800
but she only feels it when I go in deep

307
00:10:57,866 --> 00:10:59,733
to the point I think,
"I might break her bone."

308
00:10:59,800 --> 00:11:01,233
That's right.

309
00:11:01,300 --> 00:11:03,066
Also, I have to give her massages

310
00:11:03,133 --> 00:11:06,000
to keep things peaceful at home.

311
00:11:06,066 --> 00:11:06,900
Here's what I mean.

312
00:11:06,966 --> 00:11:08,200
The air at home?

313
00:11:08,266 --> 00:11:12,466
Aren't there times when your wife
puts her leg on you in her sleep?

314
00:11:12,533 --> 00:11:14,100
-That happens.
-She does that, right?

315
00:11:14,166 --> 00:11:15,466
But after she gets a massage,

316
00:11:15,533 --> 00:11:16,633
she doesn't do that.

317
00:11:16,933 --> 00:11:18,533
PROTECTING MY DEEP SLEEP…

318
00:11:18,600 --> 00:11:20,933
So you're doing it to save yourself?

319
00:11:21,000 --> 00:11:24,466
The thing is, Sang-hwa's muscles

320
00:11:24,533 --> 00:11:25,933
are crowded.

321
00:11:26,200 --> 00:11:28,933
MUSCLES LIKE NATIONAL TREASURE

322
00:11:29,000 --> 00:11:32,900
It's more crowded than you imagine.
It's stiff.

323
00:11:32,966 --> 00:11:35,800
So I have to massage her to survive.

324
00:11:35,866 --> 00:11:37,266
Only when she feels relaxed, I can sleep

325
00:11:37,333 --> 00:11:38,933
-Spill your true feelings.
-in peace.

326
00:11:39,000 --> 00:11:41,300
Wait, something is weird here.

327
00:11:41,366 --> 00:11:43,133
You're making me want to spill everything.

328
00:11:43,200 --> 00:11:44,666
Yes, it's like that.

329
00:11:44,733 --> 00:11:46,733
Sung-ju always gets it out of me.

330
00:11:46,800 --> 00:11:49,933
-He lives such a diligent life.
-All right.

331
00:11:50,000 --> 00:11:53,466
Woo-rim, in your married life,

332
00:11:53,533 --> 00:11:55,566
tell us some of moments
that make you think,

333
00:11:55,633 --> 00:11:57,233
"Right, she was an athlete."

334
00:11:57,300 --> 00:11:59,900
First of all,
her reflexes are on another level.

335
00:11:59,966 --> 00:12:02,733
-Any examples?
-For example, if something drops,

336
00:12:02,800 --> 00:12:03,800
she snatches it quickly.

337
00:12:03,866 --> 00:12:05,533
CAN TOTALLY RELATE

338
00:12:05,600 --> 00:12:06,433
Something like that.

339
00:12:06,500 --> 00:12:08,333
One day, we went to a hotel,

340
00:12:08,400 --> 00:12:10,733
and we decided to have some cup <i>ramyeon</i>.

341
00:12:10,800 --> 00:12:13,733
In the room,
there was a bar table made of marble.

342
00:12:13,800 --> 00:12:16,266
I should've been the one to lift it,

343
00:12:16,333 --> 00:12:19,433
but she lifted it immediately
and moved it over.

344
00:12:19,500 --> 00:12:20,766
A marble table?

345
00:12:20,833 --> 00:12:23,933
Most men would've volunteered
to take it from their wife,

346
00:12:24,000 --> 00:12:25,933
but she made it seem so easy,

347
00:12:26,000 --> 00:12:27,933
so I ended up making way for her.

348
00:12:28,200 --> 00:12:30,566
THIS WAY, PLEASE

349
00:12:30,633 --> 00:12:32,466
She put it down and said,

350
00:12:32,533 --> 00:12:33,633
"What are you doing?"

351
00:12:33,700 --> 00:12:36,433
-Something like that.
-I totally get it.

352
00:12:36,500 --> 00:12:40,333
Ms. Sang-hwa
also picks up heavy things so easily.

353
00:12:40,400 --> 00:12:41,466
"Ms. Sang-hwa."

354
00:12:41,533 --> 00:12:43,566
She can climb up five flights of stairs

355
00:12:43,633 --> 00:12:45,533
with me in her arms.

356
00:12:45,800 --> 00:12:46,900
THAT'S AMAZING

357
00:12:46,966 --> 00:12:50,000
-She squats up to 140 kg.
-That's amazing.

358
00:12:50,066 --> 00:12:52,000
To follow up on that snatching story,

359
00:12:52,066 --> 00:12:54,000
athletes truly are very quick.

360
00:12:54,066 --> 00:12:57,600
One day, I went to a coffee shop
with Sang-hwa, Yuna, and Woo-rim.

361
00:12:57,666 --> 00:13:00,233
You get a beeper that goes off
when your order is ready, right?

362
00:13:00,300 --> 00:13:02,366
On the very first "beep,"
they're already there.

363
00:13:02,733 --> 00:13:04,766
WHAT JUST FLEW BY?

364
00:13:04,833 --> 00:13:06,166
It was so shocking.

365
00:13:06,533 --> 00:13:08,133
SNICKERING

366
00:13:08,200 --> 00:13:09,600
I can totally see it.

367
00:13:09,666 --> 00:13:11,233
-Their reflexes are crazy.
-Immediately.

368
00:13:11,300 --> 00:13:13,733
Then they bring the coffee
and begin to scold us.

369
00:13:13,800 --> 00:13:15,200
"Why are you two sitting around?"

370
00:13:15,266 --> 00:13:16,666
-Exactly!
-Instead of getting up?

371
00:13:16,733 --> 00:13:18,333
How can we keep up with their speed?

372
00:13:18,766 --> 00:13:20,233
IT'S NOT THAT THEY DON'T, THEY CAN'T

373
00:13:20,300 --> 00:13:22,566
I would if I could,
but I can't keep up with her speed.

374
00:13:22,633 --> 00:13:24,733
They're so fast
that I can't even follow her.

375
00:13:24,800 --> 00:13:26,066
Especially Sang-hwa.

376
00:13:26,133 --> 00:13:27,966
Yes, so Yuna was right after Sang-hwa.

377
00:13:28,200 --> 00:13:31,066
DOESN'T FORGET TO BRAG ABOUT HIS WIFE

378
00:13:31,133 --> 00:13:33,566
We're with Kangnam,
the man who makes the queen mad.

379
00:13:33,633 --> 00:13:37,166
I wonder what he keeps in his fridge.

380
00:13:37,233 --> 00:13:39,900
How long has it been already?
Over a decade, right?

381
00:13:39,966 --> 00:13:40,833
Twelve years ago.

382
00:13:40,900 --> 00:13:44,766
<i>-He was on the show as our third guest.</i>
-This is awkward.

383
00:13:44,833 --> 00:13:46,366
From what I remember,

384
00:13:46,433 --> 00:13:48,500
didn't I help you clean it out?

385
00:13:48,566 --> 00:13:51,066
He actually helped me clean it
even during the break.

386
00:13:51,133 --> 00:13:52,733
You'll have a mouse at home soon.

387
00:13:52,800 --> 00:13:54,500
HIS FRIDGE WAS IN DIRE CONDITION BACK THEN

388
00:13:54,566 --> 00:13:56,566
<i>-Back then, I lived alone.</i>
<i>-Alone.</i>

389
00:13:56,633 --> 00:13:59,066
<i>-So I had lots of expired food.</i>
<i>-Yes.</i>

390
00:13:59,133 --> 00:14:02,433
I remember being quite worried
at that time.

391
00:14:02,500 --> 00:14:04,233
-But now you're married.
-Yes.

392
00:14:04,300 --> 00:14:09,133
I'm sure your fridge has been tidied up
under Sang-hwa's instruction.

393
00:14:09,200 --> 00:14:11,033
I wouldn't call it instructions.

394
00:14:11,100 --> 00:14:13,333
I'm not allowed to touch it.

395
00:14:13,633 --> 00:14:15,833
YOU CAN'T EVEN TOUCH IT?

396
00:14:15,900 --> 00:14:17,266
She glares at me when I do.

397
00:14:17,333 --> 00:14:19,033
OH, NO…

398
00:14:19,100 --> 00:14:20,433
Thinking that he might eat again.

399
00:14:20,500 --> 00:14:22,433
You can open it,
yet you can't grab anything, right?

400
00:14:22,500 --> 00:14:25,133
I can't. She keeps an eye on me
in case I eat something.

401
00:14:25,200 --> 00:14:27,400
-She's trying to keep you healthy.
-She gives me a look.

402
00:14:27,466 --> 00:14:29,300
What will Kangnam's fridge look like

403
00:14:29,366 --> 00:14:32,033
after his marriage to Sang-hwa?

404
00:14:32,100 --> 00:14:33,300
We present his fridge!

405
00:14:33,866 --> 00:14:34,833
It's filled.

406
00:14:34,900 --> 00:14:37,766
IT'S FULL

407
00:14:38,033 --> 00:14:40,300
PRESENTING KANGNAM
AND LEE SANG-HWA'S FRIDGE

408
00:14:40,366 --> 00:14:44,900
This is the fridge under
Sang-hwa's management and supervision,

409
00:14:44,966 --> 00:14:47,233
the one Kangnam isn't allowed to touch.

410
00:14:47,300 --> 00:14:50,500
The top shelf has something in Japanese.

411
00:14:50,566 --> 00:14:51,900
Did you get these from Japan?

412
00:14:51,966 --> 00:14:53,866
-Yes, rice seasoning.
-I see.

413
00:14:53,933 --> 00:14:55,966
-In the fridge?
-I can eat endless rice with that.

414
00:14:56,266 --> 00:14:58,533
MANY DIFFERENT KINDS

415
00:14:58,600 --> 00:15:00,266
These aren't usually kept in the fridge.

416
00:15:00,333 --> 00:15:02,966
Yes, it'll become soggy in the fridge,

417
00:15:03,033 --> 00:15:05,000
so it's better to keep it outside.

418
00:15:05,066 --> 00:15:06,333
Don't say that. She'll get mad.

419
00:15:08,200 --> 00:15:09,400
It must be kept in the fridge.

420
00:15:09,466 --> 00:15:11,433
-Who put these in here?
-Those?

421
00:15:11,500 --> 00:15:14,033
-I did.
-Right? You put it in here, right?

422
00:15:14,100 --> 00:15:16,366
-It wasn't Sang-hwa, was it?
-Stop it. It was me.

423
00:15:16,433 --> 00:15:19,566
-You can't say Sang-hwa did any wrong.
-No.

424
00:15:19,633 --> 00:15:21,900
This one is labeled.

425
00:15:21,966 --> 00:15:23,566
"Regular curry."

426
00:15:23,633 --> 00:15:26,066
Sang-hwa used to dislike curry,

427
00:15:26,133 --> 00:15:29,700
but she began to like them
after I made some for her.

428
00:15:29,766 --> 00:15:31,800
-She only eats curry these days.
-I see.

429
00:15:31,866 --> 00:15:33,500
What do you think this is?

430
00:15:33,566 --> 00:15:34,533
-Cabbage.
-Cabbage.

431
00:15:34,600 --> 00:15:37,300
She portioned out the cabbage.

432
00:15:37,366 --> 00:15:39,766
She loves the shabu-shabu I make.

433
00:15:39,833 --> 00:15:42,266
She'd julienne the cabbage thinly

434
00:15:42,333 --> 00:15:44,633
so we can wrap it with meat.

435
00:15:44,700 --> 00:15:47,133
-Is that so?
-This must've been Sang-hwa.

436
00:15:47,200 --> 00:15:49,233
-These are mushrooms.
-They are.

437
00:15:49,300 --> 00:15:51,433
-Shiitake.
-You have a lot of these.

438
00:15:51,500 --> 00:15:52,700
I had to lose weight,

439
00:15:52,766 --> 00:15:54,700
but I still needed some carbs
to be on variety shows.

440
00:15:54,766 --> 00:15:56,700
-Otherwise, I'd be out of energy.
-Right.

441
00:15:56,766 --> 00:15:59,466
So she made me mushroom rice,

442
00:15:59,533 --> 00:16:00,766
with 70% mushroom and 30% rice.

443
00:16:01,100 --> 00:16:02,600
EFFECTIVE FOR DIETING

444
00:16:02,666 --> 00:16:04,200
I dropped a lot of weight, thanks to that.

445
00:16:04,266 --> 00:16:06,200
I'm trying to lose a lot more right now.

446
00:16:06,266 --> 00:16:08,066
You look good now, though. How much more?

447
00:16:08,133 --> 00:16:11,400
If I don't work out,

448
00:16:11,466 --> 00:16:13,833
I'll turn out just like Jung-hwan
and gain it all back.

449
00:16:13,900 --> 00:16:15,600
Did you have to compare yourself to me?

450
00:16:15,900 --> 00:16:17,733
HE HAD TO…

451
00:16:17,800 --> 00:16:20,500
-You were really handsome in the old days.
-That's true.

452
00:16:20,566 --> 00:16:22,933
But now, he's just like that
since he has stopped trying.

453
00:16:23,166 --> 00:16:24,500
JUST. LIKE. THAT.

454
00:16:24,766 --> 00:16:25,833
YOU MIGHT TURN OUT LIKE HIM

455
00:16:25,900 --> 00:16:27,066
I'd love to look like him.

456
00:16:27,133 --> 00:16:29,633
I was also a K-pop idol,
so I need to take care of myself.

457
00:16:29,700 --> 00:16:31,833
Does Sang-hwa enjoy vegetables?

458
00:16:31,900 --> 00:16:33,600
She does…

459
00:16:33,666 --> 00:16:34,600
What's with your voice?

460
00:16:34,833 --> 00:16:36,300
IT SUDDENLY SOUNDED TOO CHIRPY

461
00:16:36,366 --> 00:16:38,966
-"Vegetables?"
-You don't seem to like it.

462
00:16:39,033 --> 00:16:41,466
-She forces…
-You end up mimicking the guest's tone.

463
00:16:41,533 --> 00:16:44,133
Your voice was lower
when you were talking to him.

464
00:16:44,200 --> 00:16:45,033
-It happens.
-It does?

465
00:16:45,233 --> 00:16:46,666
COULDN'T CONTROL HIS CHIRPY TONE

466
00:16:46,733 --> 00:16:49,500
-My voice keeps going up with you.
-He's adapting to you.

467
00:16:49,566 --> 00:16:52,200
You don't seem like the type
who likes vegetables.

468
00:16:52,266 --> 00:16:54,266
-I only like to eat meat.
-Meat.

469
00:16:54,333 --> 00:16:57,133
But Sang-hwa tries her best
to feed me veggies.

470
00:16:57,200 --> 00:16:58,566
What do you eat in the morning?

471
00:16:58,633 --> 00:17:00,500
She gives me something like oatmeal.

472
00:17:00,566 --> 00:17:02,833
-Oatmeal.
-Oatmeal.

473
00:17:02,900 --> 00:17:05,800
-Yes, I found oatmeal.
-What is that?

474
00:17:05,866 --> 00:17:09,533
-Do you eat this for breakfast?
-Yes, she soaks it

475
00:17:09,599 --> 00:17:12,933
and makes it delicious
with cheese and onion.

476
00:17:13,000 --> 00:17:15,233
-Wait a minute.
-They must order lots of delivery food.

477
00:17:15,300 --> 00:17:17,300
These are signs of delivery food.

478
00:17:17,366 --> 00:17:20,433
-I can't even order delivery food now.
-Why not?

479
00:17:20,500 --> 00:17:22,200
She didn't let me register
my credit card on the app.

480
00:17:22,266 --> 00:17:23,599
What?

481
00:17:23,666 --> 00:17:27,566
It seems like she orders
and eats delivery food while I'm away.

482
00:17:27,633 --> 00:17:28,766
Wait a minute.

483
00:17:28,833 --> 00:17:30,833
She doesn't let her husband

484
00:17:30,900 --> 00:17:33,433
-register the credit card on his phone?
-No.

485
00:17:33,500 --> 00:17:37,766
If I have to order something,
I have to call her and have her do it.

486
00:17:37,833 --> 00:17:39,433
Doesn't she sound like a manager

487
00:17:39,500 --> 00:17:42,033
-for an A-list K-pop idol group?
-Yes.

488
00:17:42,100 --> 00:17:43,233
She's like the CEO of an agency.

489
00:17:43,300 --> 00:17:45,266
Which is harder, your idol days or now?

490
00:17:45,333 --> 00:17:46,900
It's much harder these days.

491
00:17:48,633 --> 00:17:51,666
Sang-hwa could never enjoy
delivery food as an athlete.

492
00:17:51,733 --> 00:17:53,233
I'm sure it was the same for Yuna.

493
00:17:53,300 --> 00:17:56,400
So she enjoys that by herself
when I'm away.

494
00:17:56,466 --> 00:18:00,766
So if you call and ask,
does she let you order delivery food?

495
00:18:00,833 --> 00:18:02,533
No, there's a process.

496
00:18:02,600 --> 00:18:04,066
First, I need to have a good reason.

497
00:18:04,133 --> 00:18:06,033
-You need to convince her.
-For example,

498
00:18:06,100 --> 00:18:07,800
I might be very sad on that day.

499
00:18:07,866 --> 00:18:10,966
-I need an excuse like that.
-You need a story.

500
00:18:11,033 --> 00:18:14,066
I explain that the crew for
my YouTube channel is having a tough time

501
00:18:14,133 --> 00:18:16,166
for about five minutes, and she lets me.

502
00:18:16,233 --> 00:18:18,200
I need to present a good reason.

503
00:18:18,266 --> 00:18:20,766
If I randomly crave <i>jjajangmyeon,</i>
she never lets me eat it.

504
00:18:20,833 --> 00:18:22,866
ON TOP OF THAT

505
00:18:22,933 --> 00:18:25,566
I also need to promise
that I'll run 15 km the next day.

506
00:18:25,800 --> 00:18:27,333
IT'S TOUGH TO GET DELIVERY FOOD

507
00:18:27,400 --> 00:18:29,233
<i>Jjajangmyeon</i> is about 15 km.

508
00:18:29,300 --> 00:18:31,766
But when I go to a buffet,
I need to make it 20 km.

509
00:18:31,833 --> 00:18:33,566
MENU PRICING

510
00:18:33,633 --> 00:18:36,833
So I often practice my art of persuasion.

511
00:18:36,900 --> 00:18:39,366
I rarely order delivery,
maybe once every six months.

512
00:18:40,066 --> 00:18:41,233
But frankly,

513
00:18:41,300 --> 00:18:43,500
she's not around
when you're working outside,

514
00:18:43,566 --> 00:18:45,300
so you can eat it in secret
with someone else.

515
00:18:45,366 --> 00:18:46,700
Has that ever happened?

516
00:18:46,766 --> 00:18:51,633
My managers at the agency
have nothing to do with Sang-hwa.

517
00:18:51,700 --> 00:18:54,933
But they still
report everything back to her!

518
00:18:55,000 --> 00:18:56,700
So she knows what you're eating.

519
00:18:56,766 --> 00:18:58,100
So after my workday, she'd ask,

520
00:18:58,166 --> 00:18:59,333
"Why did you eat that?"

521
00:18:59,566 --> 00:19:00,666
SHUDDER

522
00:19:00,733 --> 00:19:02,166
She's way up there.

523
00:19:02,233 --> 00:19:04,666
-She has everyone under control.
-She does.

524
00:19:04,733 --> 00:19:06,600
-The managers and Kangnam.
-Yes.

525
00:19:06,666 --> 00:19:09,566
He says that, but he's a huge romantic.

526
00:19:09,633 --> 00:19:11,300
-He's just joking around.
-Really?

527
00:19:11,366 --> 00:19:13,333
Keep saying stuff like that.

528
00:19:13,400 --> 00:19:15,766
-Right.
-He exaggerates to make it funny.

529
00:19:15,833 --> 00:19:18,266
-Intentionally.
-He does it to joke around.

530
00:19:18,333 --> 00:19:20,666
Is there anything

531
00:19:20,733 --> 00:19:23,100
that Yuna wants you to do?

532
00:19:23,166 --> 00:19:26,000
I rarely remember to take my vitamins.

533
00:19:26,066 --> 00:19:27,200
She brings them

534
00:19:27,266 --> 00:19:30,833
and reminds me to eat them,
but I sometimes forget and leave.

535
00:19:30,900 --> 00:19:34,100
Then she scolds me
and tells me that I have to.

536
00:19:34,166 --> 00:19:37,766
We're like that too.
She always gets the vitamins for me,

537
00:19:37,833 --> 00:19:39,233
but I don't want to take them.

538
00:19:39,300 --> 00:19:42,033
Let's say she's sitting over there.

539
00:19:42,100 --> 00:19:44,000
Then she throws them at me.

540
00:19:45,166 --> 00:19:46,400
-"Eat it!"
-The vitamins?

541
00:19:46,466 --> 00:19:49,633
-So I catch and eat them.
-With your mouth?

542
00:19:49,700 --> 00:19:52,266
-Just like that.
-Why would you do that?

543
00:19:52,333 --> 00:19:56,066
I'm probably the best at catching
and eating whatever's thrown at me.

544
00:19:56,133 --> 00:19:57,533
I'm so good at it.

545
00:19:57,600 --> 00:20:00,733
I can catch and eat
tiny vitamin pills like this.

546
00:20:00,800 --> 00:20:03,333
The third shelf. I see some kimchi.

547
00:20:03,900 --> 00:20:06,133
This must be sour kimchi.

548
00:20:06,200 --> 00:20:08,300
-Sour kimchi.
-You ate a lot of it.

549
00:20:08,366 --> 00:20:10,000
I like sour kimchi.

550
00:20:10,066 --> 00:20:11,633
-Is this what you like?
-Yes.

551
00:20:11,700 --> 00:20:14,266
I recently came to like

552
00:20:14,333 --> 00:20:15,933
refreshing dishes.

553
00:20:16,000 --> 00:20:17,433
That's it.

554
00:20:17,500 --> 00:20:21,666
I was raised in Japan, so I didn't get
the concept of refreshing dishes.

555
00:20:21,733 --> 00:20:22,666
Right. "Refreshing."

556
00:20:22,733 --> 00:20:24,600
People here say
cold dishes are refreshing,

557
00:20:24,666 --> 00:20:26,733
but they also say that to hot dishes,

558
00:20:26,800 --> 00:20:28,466
and even when they go into a hot tub.

559
00:20:28,733 --> 00:20:30,766
A WORD NOT REFRESHINGLY DEFINED

560
00:20:30,833 --> 00:20:33,833
My old agency's CEO came to Japan,

561
00:20:33,900 --> 00:20:36,700
drank the night before,
and went to an udon place with me.

562
00:20:36,766 --> 00:20:38,833
He told me to order something refreshing,

563
00:20:38,900 --> 00:20:40,666
so I ordered five bowls of cold udon.

564
00:20:40,900 --> 00:20:42,533
A REFRESHING MISCOMMUNICATION

565
00:20:42,600 --> 00:20:43,733
He went, "You dummy,"

566
00:20:43,800 --> 00:20:45,333
and got really mad at me.

567
00:20:45,600 --> 00:20:47,333
HE ONLY ORDERED REFRESHINGLY ICY DISHES…

568
00:20:47,400 --> 00:20:49,666
I thought it had to have ice
to be refreshing.

569
00:20:49,733 --> 00:20:52,200
So I didn't really get the concept
back then.

570
00:20:52,266 --> 00:20:53,100
Understandable.

571
00:20:53,166 --> 00:20:55,700
But now I know what it means,

572
00:20:55,766 --> 00:20:58,600
and I always need sour kimchi
to eat with something refreshing.

573
00:20:58,666 --> 00:21:01,500
-It's invigorating.
-Yes, the invigorating flavor.

574
00:21:01,566 --> 00:21:02,766
Broccoli.

575
00:21:02,833 --> 00:21:03,866
Avocado.

576
00:21:03,933 --> 00:21:05,166
Do you have a favorite vegetable?

577
00:21:05,233 --> 00:21:08,400
I don't particularly like veggies,
but I like avocados.

578
00:21:08,466 --> 00:21:11,000
-Avocados.
-When I chop them up

579
00:21:11,066 --> 00:21:14,533
and pour soy sauce over them,
they taste like <i>otoro</i>.

580
00:21:14,600 --> 00:21:16,066
-Yes, people eat it like that.
-Yes.

581
00:21:16,133 --> 00:21:17,933
-It tastes like fish.
-What's <i>otoro?</i>

582
00:21:18,000 --> 00:21:19,966
-Fatty tuna belly.
-Oh, tuna.

583
00:21:20,033 --> 00:21:24,000
Go and eat something expensive.
You're a rich man.

584
00:21:24,066 --> 00:21:27,466
I would've understood if you called it
tuna belly, not <i>otoro</i>. That's Japanese.

585
00:21:27,533 --> 00:21:29,533
He hosts a classy cooking show,

586
00:21:29,600 --> 00:21:31,333
but he knows nothing
about food ingredients.

587
00:21:31,600 --> 00:21:33,833
SHEEPISH

588
00:21:33,900 --> 00:21:35,533
-Sure. <i>Otoru</i>.
-"<i>Otoro</i>."

589
00:21:35,600 --> 00:21:40,133
When I lived in Hawaii,
I always had bboki with avocado and tuna.

590
00:21:40,200 --> 00:21:41,966
-I see.
-Right. Poke.

591
00:21:42,033 --> 00:21:43,266
-Poke, not bboki.
-Yes, poke.

592
00:21:43,333 --> 00:21:44,500
That's on you.

593
00:21:44,566 --> 00:21:45,933
HOLDING A GRUDGE

594
00:21:46,533 --> 00:21:48,500
You're both waiting
for each other's mishaps.

595
00:21:48,566 --> 00:21:51,300
-Go and eat some poke. You're rich.
-I got one thing wrong.

596
00:21:51,366 --> 00:21:53,733
-"Poke."
-Yes, poke.

597
00:21:53,800 --> 00:21:56,133
Now, the freezer.

598
00:21:56,200 --> 00:21:57,700
What's this?

599
00:21:58,033 --> 00:21:59,533
A PILE OF ICE CREAM

600
00:21:59,600 --> 00:22:01,366
Why do you have so much ice cream?

601
00:22:01,433 --> 00:22:04,700
Everything there
solely belongs to Sang-hwa.

602
00:22:04,766 --> 00:22:06,833
-What?
-Not mine.

603
00:22:06,900 --> 00:22:10,800
I opened up a whole different world to her
as soon as she retired,

604
00:22:10,866 --> 00:22:12,766
to desserts and sorts.

605
00:22:12,833 --> 00:22:16,766
I let her try this and that,
and she ended up eating too much.

606
00:22:16,833 --> 00:22:20,200
I think she likes having them around.
It makes her happy.

607
00:22:20,266 --> 00:22:23,333
Because she couldn't eat those
when she was an athlete.

608
00:22:23,900 --> 00:22:24,933
You can have them with her.

609
00:22:25,000 --> 00:22:27,000
I'd be in deep trouble.
I cannot touch those.

610
00:22:28,733 --> 00:22:31,400
-Those are Sang-hwa's treasures.
-But she has so many.

611
00:22:31,466 --> 00:22:32,833
If I eat it…

612
00:22:32,900 --> 00:22:34,400
If I eat even one, she notices.

613
00:22:34,466 --> 00:22:36,566
-She must've counted them.
-She can tell.

614
00:22:36,633 --> 00:22:39,900
-She has an insanely accurate memory.
-It's her collection.

615
00:22:39,966 --> 00:22:43,133
But her plans always turn out so well.

616
00:22:43,200 --> 00:22:45,600
I lost weight, lost my fatty liver,

617
00:22:45,666 --> 00:22:47,400
and my cholesterol level dropped.

618
00:22:47,466 --> 00:22:50,133
-All she says is correct.
-Right?

619
00:22:50,200 --> 00:22:51,466
All right.

620
00:22:51,533 --> 00:22:54,066
Let's take a look
at the shelf-stable ingredients.

621
00:22:54,133 --> 00:22:55,600
Rice paper.

622
00:22:55,666 --> 00:22:57,666
-Do you wrap veggies with these?
-Yes.

623
00:22:57,733 --> 00:23:00,700
-She makes them for me.
-He has rice paper.

624
00:23:00,766 --> 00:23:02,833
And all kinds of sauces.

625
00:23:02,900 --> 00:23:04,966
I also see quite a few
Japanese ingredients.

626
00:23:05,033 --> 00:23:06,966
That was all for Kangnam's fridge!

627
00:23:07,033 --> 00:23:09,100
FINISHED CHECKING OUT
KANGNAM AND LEE SANG-HWA'S FRIDGE

628
00:23:09,166 --> 00:23:11,700
And now, let's find out
what Kangnam wants to eat today.

629
00:23:11,766 --> 00:23:14,366
Show us Kangnam's orders!

630
00:23:14,433 --> 00:23:15,666
Kangnam's orders.

631
00:23:15,733 --> 00:23:18,500
A DISH LEE SANG-HWA WOULD LOVE,
A DISH LEE SANG-HWA WOULD HATE

632
00:23:18,566 --> 00:23:20,500
A dish Lee Sang-hwa would love,

633
00:23:20,566 --> 00:23:22,333
a dish Lee Sang-hwa would hate.

634
00:23:22,400 --> 00:23:24,266
Aren't those perfect?

635
00:23:24,533 --> 00:23:26,033
TYPICAL OF KANGNAM

636
00:23:26,100 --> 00:23:27,966
-They're so clear.
-It's clear.

637
00:23:28,033 --> 00:23:29,266
In other words,

638
00:23:29,333 --> 00:23:32,100
the first one
is a dish Kangnam would hate,

639
00:23:32,166 --> 00:23:34,700
and the next one
is a dish Kangnam would love.

640
00:23:34,766 --> 00:23:36,833
-You're right.
-That's what these mean.

641
00:23:36,900 --> 00:23:40,800
First, something Sang-hwa would love.
Something she'd see and find healthy

642
00:23:40,866 --> 00:23:44,466
and would want me to eat.

643
00:23:44,533 --> 00:23:47,433
Something good for dieting yet filling.

644
00:23:47,500 --> 00:23:49,766
The next one
is A Dish Lee Sang-hwa Would Hate.

645
00:23:49,833 --> 00:23:52,233
We humored her with the first dish,

646
00:23:52,300 --> 00:23:55,200
so make me something
she would absolutely hate next.

647
00:23:55,266 --> 00:23:58,866
Something with a huge amount of carbs.

648
00:23:58,933 --> 00:24:02,600
-Why are you looking right at me?
-You know, lots of meat! You know, right?

649
00:24:02,666 --> 00:24:04,266
Throw everything in!

650
00:24:04,333 --> 00:24:05,866
-Bam!
-Something rich.

651
00:24:05,933 --> 00:24:07,266
-Boom.
-Yes, that.

652
00:24:07,333 --> 00:24:09,233
Something like that.

653
00:24:09,300 --> 00:24:13,233
I want to see a pile of food
on top of a pile of rice.

654
00:24:13,300 --> 00:24:15,766
-Don't you dare use oatmeal.
-What do you mean?

655
00:24:15,833 --> 00:24:18,633
Why is everyone talking to me?
I didn't say I'd join that round.

656
00:24:18,700 --> 00:24:20,866
I could go for the top one.

657
00:24:20,933 --> 00:24:22,833
Anyone can expect Poong to join

658
00:24:22,900 --> 00:24:24,866
-A Dish Lee Sang-hwa Would Hate.
-What she'd hate.

659
00:24:24,933 --> 00:24:26,366
He's Evil Poong.

660
00:24:26,433 --> 00:24:30,233
-I'll join A Dish Lee Sang-hwa Would Hate.
-What she'd hate. Let's put him down.

661
00:24:30,300 --> 00:24:32,800
-Poong is set.
-A dish Kangnam would love.

662
00:24:32,866 --> 00:24:35,900
Three chefs remain,
Ho-young, Eun-yeong, and Sung-jun.

663
00:24:35,966 --> 00:24:37,933
-Me. I'll go.
-Chef Eun-yeong?

664
00:24:38,000 --> 00:24:40,666
-The healthy one?
-A Dish Lee Sang-hwa Would Hate.

665
00:24:40,733 --> 00:24:42,400
-Whoa!
-What?

666
00:24:42,466 --> 00:24:44,633
-It's because…
-She's strong against Poong.

667
00:24:44,700 --> 00:24:46,700
…it has been a while
since I've won a star.

668
00:24:46,766 --> 00:24:49,100
-So I must win one today.
-It was to win a star?

669
00:24:49,166 --> 00:24:51,466
It'd be wiser for me to join his round.

670
00:24:51,533 --> 00:24:52,933
Six wins in a row?

671
00:24:53,000 --> 00:24:55,066
-I have six stars.
-She can easily beat him.

672
00:24:55,133 --> 00:24:56,766
Then it's settled.

673
00:24:56,833 --> 00:25:00,033
-Ho-young and Sung-jun, healthy dishes.
-And Sung-jun.

674
00:25:00,100 --> 00:25:02,266
-You're right.
-It's settled.

675
00:25:02,333 --> 00:25:05,366
I don't think Ho-young can make
something Sang-hwa will love.

676
00:25:05,433 --> 00:25:07,900
-I was too late.
-You missed your chance.

677
00:25:07,966 --> 00:25:09,866
You have to make something she'd like.

678
00:25:09,933 --> 00:25:12,266
-I'll try to imagine a dish like that.
-"Imagine"?

679
00:25:12,333 --> 00:25:14,233
-All right.
-It's settled.

680
00:25:14,300 --> 00:25:17,600
First, let us begin the cook-off
between Ho-young and Sung-jun!

681
00:25:18,033 --> 00:25:20,966
IT'LL BEGIN NOW!

682
00:25:21,633 --> 00:25:26,000
<i>This is the first round of cook-off</i>
<i>with ingredients from Kangnam's fridge.</i>

683
00:25:26,066 --> 00:25:29,833
A guy who loves dancing
more than stars, Chef Jung Ho-young,

684
00:25:29,900 --> 00:25:32,333
versus a guy who wants

685
00:25:32,400 --> 00:25:34,400
more followers than stars,
Chef Kwon Sung-jun.

686
00:25:34,466 --> 00:25:36,733
The CFF. Crazy for followers.

687
00:25:36,800 --> 00:25:40,733
-Is that why they don't have many stars?
-That's right.

688
00:25:40,800 --> 00:25:42,700
They aren't hung up on the stars.

689
00:25:42,766 --> 00:25:45,933
-Here's a shocking fact before we begin.
-What is it?

690
00:25:46,000 --> 00:25:49,466
This is the first cook-off
between these two chefs.

691
00:25:49,533 --> 00:25:51,433
-Really?
-It's been a year and a half.

692
00:25:51,500 --> 00:25:52,900
-How did that happen?
-The first.

693
00:25:52,966 --> 00:25:54,366
It's the first time ever?

694
00:25:54,433 --> 00:25:58,666
But Chef Sung-jun said
he's been wanting to take on Ho-young.

695
00:25:58,733 --> 00:26:00,633
-Wasn't he his master?
-His former master.

696
00:26:00,700 --> 00:26:02,333
Everyone here is his former master.

697
00:26:02,400 --> 00:26:04,900
-He wanted to side with Ho-young before.
-I think

698
00:26:04,966 --> 00:26:06,966
it's about time to switch my master,

699
00:26:07,033 --> 00:26:08,533
because Teacher's Day is soon.

700
00:26:08,600 --> 00:26:10,933
-So I'll have a go at him.
-"A go"?

701
00:26:11,233 --> 00:26:12,300
A DAY TO DEFY THE MASTER

702
00:26:12,366 --> 00:26:13,733
He'll have a go at his master?

703
00:26:13,800 --> 00:26:15,866
I want to win and switch masters.

704
00:26:15,933 --> 00:26:17,366
The student becomes the master.

705
00:26:17,433 --> 00:26:19,500
-He should surpass his master.
-So ungrateful.

706
00:26:19,566 --> 00:26:21,666
-And reckless.
-I don't understand

707
00:26:21,733 --> 00:26:25,300
why he began to call me his master.

708
00:26:25,366 --> 00:26:28,400
-He once made udon, and that was all.
-Come to think of it…

709
00:26:28,466 --> 00:26:31,433
After that day, he'd greet me by saying,
"Hello, Master."

710
00:26:31,500 --> 00:26:32,966
He never greeted me before then,

711
00:26:33,033 --> 00:26:35,400
but he does it all the time now.

712
00:26:35,466 --> 00:26:37,366
He thought, "Wait, I was his master?"

713
00:26:37,433 --> 00:26:39,300
Actually, there is someone
I have my eyes on.

714
00:26:39,366 --> 00:26:40,800
I already called dibs.

715
00:26:40,866 --> 00:26:41,900
Who is it?

716
00:26:41,966 --> 00:26:44,366
-Chef Sam.
-Chef Sam.

717
00:26:44,433 --> 00:26:47,166
-He's been winning lots of stars,
-He took Hyun-suk down last week.

718
00:26:47,233 --> 00:26:49,133
and he has gathered
many new followers too.

719
00:26:49,200 --> 00:26:52,566
-So I want to be his pupil.
-Are you free to take him?

720
00:26:52,633 --> 00:26:54,533
He's not doing that to learn cooking.

721
00:26:54,600 --> 00:26:58,233
He wants to switch over
because he's become more popular recently.

722
00:26:58,300 --> 00:26:59,866
Sam, are you willing to take him?

723
00:26:59,933 --> 00:27:02,333
-After all, he's an Italian chef.
-Master.

724
00:27:02,400 --> 00:27:04,166
-We have something in common.
-Right.

725
00:27:04,233 --> 00:27:06,133
-You do have much in common.
-You do.

726
00:27:06,200 --> 00:27:08,700
Chef Sam, why are you wearing gloves?

727
00:27:08,766 --> 00:27:10,300
-These?
-Wait.

728
00:27:10,366 --> 00:27:11,866
He asked for help.

729
00:27:11,933 --> 00:27:14,800
It's as if Ho-young is starting
with an extra cooking tool here.

730
00:27:14,866 --> 00:27:17,066
-What is this? Are you a tool now?
-Are you his tool?

731
00:27:17,133 --> 00:27:18,366
Have you become a tool?

732
00:27:18,433 --> 00:27:20,833
He wouldn't get any screen time
if it weren't for me.

733
00:27:21,600 --> 00:27:22,433
It's true.

734
00:27:22,500 --> 00:27:24,100
-It's for his screen time?
-Yes.

735
00:27:24,166 --> 00:27:26,166
He doesn't talk,
so he's never seen on the screen.

736
00:27:26,233 --> 00:27:29,533
Then Chef Sung-jun,
do you also need Nam-no to do anything?

737
00:27:29,600 --> 00:27:30,933
Not really.

738
00:27:31,633 --> 00:27:33,400
I wasn't going to do it anyway.

739
00:27:34,766 --> 00:27:37,500
You'll have to make a healthy dish

740
00:27:37,566 --> 00:27:39,566
which Lee Sang-hwa would love.

741
00:27:39,633 --> 00:27:42,933
Chef Sung-jun,
do you feel confident about this order?

742
00:27:43,000 --> 00:27:43,866
Of course.

743
00:27:43,933 --> 00:27:45,766
As you can see, I have recently

744
00:27:45,833 --> 00:27:47,266
lost some weight.

745
00:27:47,333 --> 00:27:48,733
-Really?
-What?

746
00:27:48,800 --> 00:27:50,533
-Just a little?
-That's unexpected.

747
00:27:50,600 --> 00:27:54,333
-His body seems smaller, but not his face.
-I've recently lost

748
00:27:54,400 --> 00:27:57,033
-about 6 to 7 kg.
-That's a lot.

749
00:27:57,100 --> 00:27:59,533
-How much do you weigh?
-I did it solely through dieting.

750
00:27:59,600 --> 00:28:02,266
So I know I can make
a healthy dish for weight loss.

751
00:28:02,333 --> 00:28:04,100
Does this mean he just has a big face?

752
00:28:04,166 --> 00:28:05,166
I guess so.

753
00:28:05,233 --> 00:28:06,400
He has a bigger frame.

754
00:28:06,466 --> 00:28:08,966
He lost 7 kg, but he hasn't changed much.

755
00:28:09,033 --> 00:28:10,700
ACHIEVEMENT NOT TOO NOTICEABLE

756
00:28:10,766 --> 00:28:12,433
You even said this in the back.

757
00:28:12,500 --> 00:28:15,600
"Chef Ho-young probably doesn't even know
what diet food is like."

758
00:28:15,666 --> 00:28:16,666
Did you say that?

759
00:28:16,733 --> 00:28:17,733
That is

760
00:28:17,800 --> 00:28:19,133
absolutely something I said.

761
00:28:20,866 --> 00:28:22,233
You said those words?

762
00:28:22,300 --> 00:28:23,933
Yes, those exact words.

763
00:28:24,000 --> 00:28:25,833
-Are you looking down on him?
-It's not that.

764
00:28:25,900 --> 00:28:28,866
I believe he's someone
who works out to raise his appetite…

765
00:28:28,933 --> 00:28:31,633
-"To raise his appetite."
-…not someone who eats diet food.

766
00:28:31,700 --> 00:28:33,000
I know

767
00:28:33,066 --> 00:28:36,333
more about diet food than anybody,
but I just don't put it to practice.

768
00:28:36,400 --> 00:28:39,166
My wife is also like Sang-hwa,

769
00:28:39,233 --> 00:28:41,433
so she always tells me,
"Don't eat anything greasy."

770
00:28:41,500 --> 00:28:43,000
-"Don't eat too much food."
-Right.

771
00:28:43,066 --> 00:28:44,000
-"Just don't eat."
-Right.

772
00:28:44,066 --> 00:28:46,033
She keeps telling me what not to do.

773
00:28:46,100 --> 00:28:48,066
-"Just don't eat"?
-So I get what it's like.

774
00:28:48,133 --> 00:28:49,933
You may have an advantage there.

775
00:28:50,766 --> 00:28:52,800
CHEF HO-YOUNG'S INGREDIENTS:
CARROT, CUCUMBER, LETTUCE, AVOCADO

776
00:28:52,866 --> 00:28:54,933
DRUMSTICK, PORK BELLY,
PICKLED GREEN PLUM, RICE PAPER, AND MORE

777
00:28:55,000 --> 00:28:58,300
You're about to make
something Sang-hwa would love.

778
00:28:58,366 --> 00:29:00,766
The name of my dish is as follows.

779
00:29:00,833 --> 00:29:02,966
Sang-hwa-licious Roll.

780
00:29:03,033 --> 00:29:05,266
-Sang-hwa-licious Roll.
-Sang-hwa-licious Roll.

781
00:29:05,333 --> 00:29:08,166
-Sang-hwa-licious.
-Sang-hwa-licious.

782
00:29:08,233 --> 00:29:11,033
-Sang-hwa-licious?
-I'll make a roll Sang-hwa would love.

783
00:29:11,100 --> 00:29:12,066
Rolls are nice.

784
00:29:12,133 --> 00:29:13,766
He mentioned that

785
00:29:13,833 --> 00:29:17,366
she often rolled vegetables in rice paper,

786
00:29:17,433 --> 00:29:20,200
but it'd be too boring
to eat just those rolls.

787
00:29:20,266 --> 00:29:21,766
There's a Japanese dish named <i>tsukune</i>,

788
00:29:21,833 --> 00:29:24,966
which I'll make by grinding
pork belly and drumstick meat.

789
00:29:25,033 --> 00:29:28,466
I'm going to grill those
and put them inside the rolls.

790
00:29:28,533 --> 00:29:30,400
Once you take a bite,

791
00:29:30,466 --> 00:29:32,800
not only will you taste the vegetables,

792
00:29:32,866 --> 00:29:34,600
but you'll also taste juicy meat.

793
00:29:34,666 --> 00:29:36,766
And Sam will help me with the sauce
which will be made

794
00:29:36,833 --> 00:29:39,033
with <i>umeboshi</i>, Japanese pickled plums.

795
00:29:39,100 --> 00:29:42,066
-He just said he'd help.
-It'll serve as a dip for the rolls.

796
00:29:42,366 --> 00:29:45,033
A DISH FOR KANGNAM'S HEALTH
AND SAM'S SCREEN TIME

797
00:29:45,866 --> 00:29:47,933
CHEF SUNG-JUN'S INGREDIENTS:
OATMEAL, SHRIMP, TOFU, SOFT TOFU

798
00:29:48,000 --> 00:29:50,033
BUTTON MUSHROOM, BROCCOLI,
CHERRY TOMATO, PARMESAN POWDER, AND MORE

799
00:29:50,100 --> 00:29:53,600
Chef Sung-jun is up against him.
What are you making?

800
00:29:53,666 --> 00:29:55,133
My dish is called

801
00:29:55,200 --> 00:29:56,933
Sang-hwa-licious Risotto.

802
00:29:57,000 --> 00:29:59,133
-Sang-hwa-licious Risotto.
-Sang-hwa-licious Risotto.

803
00:29:59,200 --> 00:30:01,500
-And he made it sound cute.
-Yes.

804
00:30:01,566 --> 00:30:04,133
-I'm making risotto.
-Risotto.

805
00:30:04,200 --> 00:30:05,066
Yes.

806
00:30:05,133 --> 00:30:07,566
I'll make risotto with oatmeal.

807
00:30:07,633 --> 00:30:09,733
-With oatmeal?
-It's for weight loss,

808
00:30:09,800 --> 00:30:11,033
but Kangnam also said

809
00:30:11,100 --> 00:30:13,066
-he has fatty liver.
-Yes.

810
00:30:13,133 --> 00:30:14,400
Those who have fatty liver

811
00:30:14,466 --> 00:30:17,066
should never have processed carbs
such as ground rice.

812
00:30:17,133 --> 00:30:20,400
-Right.
-You must keep it whole.

813
00:30:20,466 --> 00:30:22,333
So I'll use oatmeal
to make the texture of rice.

814
00:30:22,400 --> 00:30:24,166
-So no grinding.
-I'll also teach you

815
00:30:24,233 --> 00:30:27,566
how to make broccoli delicious,
since it's good for fatty liver.

816
00:30:27,633 --> 00:30:29,300
-Broccoli.
-That sounds good.

817
00:30:29,366 --> 00:30:31,366
I also plan to include a protein source

818
00:30:31,433 --> 00:30:34,333
and flame-grill it with veggies,
without using carb-heavy food.

819
00:30:34,400 --> 00:30:36,100
-I see.
-Flame-grilled.

820
00:30:36,166 --> 00:30:37,300
I was surprised

821
00:30:37,366 --> 00:30:39,200
-to hear the mention of <i>tsukune…</i>
-Yes.

822
00:30:39,266 --> 00:30:40,433
…and risotto.

823
00:30:40,500 --> 00:30:43,366
Both of them
are one of my favorite dishes.

824
00:30:43,433 --> 00:30:44,766
I'm excited for them.

825
00:30:44,833 --> 00:30:47,533
-I mean, if they can make those healthy.
-Yes.

826
00:30:47,600 --> 00:30:48,700
I'm very curious.

827
00:30:48,766 --> 00:30:50,733
All right, then.

828
00:30:50,800 --> 00:30:54,400
Let us begin their cook-off.

829
00:30:54,466 --> 00:30:58,666
The one who wants to take his master down
and keep his winning streak going,

830
00:30:58,733 --> 00:31:01,166
the ambitious chef, Kwon Sung-jun.

831
00:31:01,233 --> 00:31:04,233
The one
who never accepted Sung-jun as his pupil,

832
00:31:04,300 --> 00:31:06,066
the impregnable chef,

833
00:31:06,133 --> 00:31:08,166
Jung Ho-young is up for the battle.

834
00:31:08,233 --> 00:31:11,533
This is a one-sided Teacher's Day special.

835
00:31:11,600 --> 00:31:13,366
Who's going to rise as the winner?

836
00:31:13,433 --> 00:31:16,566
Let the 15-minute cook-off begin!

837
00:31:18,433 --> 00:31:19,433
It has begun.

838
00:31:19,900 --> 00:31:22,466
LEE SANG-HWA'S RED LIGHT, GREEN LIGHT

839
00:31:23,033 --> 00:31:24,800
HEALTHINESS RADAR ON

840
00:31:24,866 --> 00:31:26,533
…begin!

841
00:31:26,600 --> 00:31:28,366
HE BEGINS TOO

842
00:31:28,933 --> 00:31:31,766
A Dish Lee Sang-hwa Would Love.

843
00:31:31,833 --> 00:31:33,433
A healthy dish, that is.

844
00:31:33,500 --> 00:31:35,800
-Whoa, man.
-What did he pour in?

845
00:31:35,866 --> 00:31:37,666
It's cooking wine.

846
00:31:37,733 --> 00:31:40,133
Are you sure
using that much cooking wine is healthy?

847
00:31:40,200 --> 00:31:42,400
The alcohol will evaporate.

848
00:31:42,466 --> 00:31:43,500
-It'll evaporate.
-So it'll be okay.

849
00:31:43,566 --> 00:31:47,000
-The alcohol will, but the sugar…
-It'll still contain lots of sugar.

850
00:31:47,066 --> 00:31:48,866
That was the same as pouring sugar.

851
00:31:48,933 --> 00:31:50,400
What's Sam doing?

852
00:31:50,466 --> 00:31:52,100
I'm pitting the <i>umeboshi</i>.

853
00:31:52,166 --> 00:31:54,966
-He's pitting the Japanese pickled plums.
-He's pitting them.

854
00:31:55,033 --> 00:31:56,200
He's pitting them.

855
00:31:56,266 --> 00:31:57,733
-I see.
-Do you need more?

856
00:31:57,800 --> 00:31:59,166
-Yes.
-Really?

857
00:31:59,233 --> 00:32:00,100
You're doing great.

858
00:32:00,433 --> 00:32:02,300
MAKING "SOMEONE" WORK
WHILE SLICING A CARROT

859
00:32:02,866 --> 00:32:04,100
HEALTHY CARROTS

860
00:32:04,166 --> 00:32:06,400
It must be a dish
Sang-hwa would be happy to see him eat.

861
00:32:06,466 --> 00:32:08,633
-You're right.
-Yes.

862
00:32:08,700 --> 00:32:10,166
-Something healthy.
-Exactly.

863
00:32:10,233 --> 00:32:12,200
He's grilling mushrooms.

864
00:32:12,466 --> 00:32:13,666
NEXT HEALTHY VEGETABLE!

865
00:32:13,900 --> 00:32:15,966
BROCCOLI

866
00:32:16,733 --> 00:32:19,933
Sung-jun boils the broccoli.

867
00:32:21,066 --> 00:32:22,866
-That's powdered cheese.
-Cheese?

868
00:32:22,933 --> 00:32:24,933
-Powdered cheese?
-I know what he's making.

869
00:32:25,000 --> 00:32:26,666
-Crackers. Chips.
-Chips.

870
00:32:26,733 --> 00:32:29,100
-That's right.
-You can't make chips with that product.

871
00:32:29,166 --> 00:32:30,600
You can.

872
00:32:30,666 --> 00:32:32,633
-It'll fall apart.
-No, it'll work.

873
00:32:32,700 --> 00:32:34,166
-It'll happen.
-No, not tuile.

874
00:32:34,233 --> 00:32:35,266
He can make tuile.

875
00:32:35,333 --> 00:32:37,100
-Maybe it's something else.
-It's for tuile.

876
00:32:37,166 --> 00:32:40,066
Have you made it using that?
Oh, he's using cheese slices too.

877
00:32:40,133 --> 00:32:42,933
-It will happen.
-I haven't, so I'm not so sure.

878
00:32:43,000 --> 00:32:45,700
-American cheese? Then it's possible.
-He can do it.

879
00:32:45,766 --> 00:32:47,300
But not with the powder alone.

880
00:32:47,366 --> 00:32:49,066
The slices should go at the bottom.

881
00:32:49,133 --> 00:32:53,300
There's a bit of controversy
on what Sung-jun is making right now.

882
00:32:53,566 --> 00:32:54,433
WHAT'S HO-YOUNG DOING?

883
00:32:54,800 --> 00:32:56,633
CHOPPING A CUCUMBER

884
00:32:57,100 --> 00:32:58,266
1. PUT JULIENNED CUCUMBER IN WATER

885
00:32:58,333 --> 00:32:59,633
What's that? A cucumber?

886
00:32:59,700 --> 00:33:01,500
-Julienned cucumber.
-Julienned cucumber.

887
00:33:02,066 --> 00:33:03,900
The slices look really pretty.

888
00:33:03,966 --> 00:33:05,600
He used a slicer.

889
00:33:05,666 --> 00:33:08,466
-He did?
-Yes, he used a slicer.

890
00:33:08,533 --> 00:33:09,700
I saw him.

891
00:33:09,766 --> 00:33:10,933
QUICKLY SNITCHING

892
00:33:11,000 --> 00:33:12,100
You're telling on him?

893
00:33:12,166 --> 00:33:13,733
They make good slicers these days.

894
00:33:13,800 --> 00:33:16,633
-We thought he did it himself.
-We thought he did.

895
00:33:17,566 --> 00:33:19,333
NEXT, CHERRY TOMATOES!

896
00:33:19,400 --> 00:33:20,833
What's he doing with the tomatoes?

897
00:33:20,900 --> 00:33:24,433
He mixed it with olive oil, salt,
ground pepper, and a bit of sugar.

898
00:33:24,500 --> 00:33:28,033
-He's roasting them in an air fryer.
-He's using an air fryer?

899
00:33:28,100 --> 00:33:30,266
I'm going to dry them a little.

900
00:33:30,500 --> 00:33:32,133
I SEE

901
00:33:32,200 --> 00:33:35,600
You can dry them in an air fryer?

902
00:33:35,666 --> 00:33:39,266
Yes, it'll bring out the flavors,
sweetness, and sourness.

903
00:33:39,833 --> 00:33:42,266
So far, it seems like something
Sang-hwa would love.

904
00:33:42,333 --> 00:33:45,200
Sam, are you done?
You took your gloves off.

905
00:33:45,266 --> 00:33:46,200
Yes.

906
00:33:46,266 --> 00:33:48,133
Then you can go home now.

907
00:33:48,400 --> 00:33:49,900
GOT ENOUGH SCREEN TIME FOR TODAY

908
00:33:49,966 --> 00:33:52,933
-And now…
-Are you deboning that?

909
00:33:53,000 --> 00:33:55,233
-Deboning.
-He's deboning.

910
00:33:55,300 --> 00:33:56,900
CUTS OFF JUST THE MEAT

911
00:33:57,466 --> 00:33:58,833
-Pork.
-Pork belly.

912
00:33:58,900 --> 00:34:01,833
GRIND DRUMSTICK MEAT, PORK BELLY, ONION,
GREEN ONION, TSUYU, SESAME OIL, STARCH

913
00:34:01,900 --> 00:34:03,100
<i>-Tsuyu.</i>
<i>-Tsuyu.</i>

914
00:34:05,700 --> 00:34:07,633
What will you do with that ground meat?

915
00:34:07,700 --> 00:34:09,966
<i>-Tsukune.</i>
<i>-Tsukune.</i>

916
00:34:10,033 --> 00:34:12,233
Japanese-style chicken skewer places
usually serve them.

917
00:34:12,300 --> 00:34:14,400
You dip them in soy sauce and egg yolk.

918
00:34:14,466 --> 00:34:15,400
THAT SOUNDS GOOD

919
00:34:15,466 --> 00:34:19,033
-Kangnam must be familiar with it.
-Yes.

920
00:34:19,100 --> 00:34:22,033
TSUKUNE SHAPED INTO A LONG ROLL

921
00:34:22,100 --> 00:34:23,866
Ho-young cooks the <i>tsukune</i>.

922
00:34:23,933 --> 00:34:25,400
Twelve minutes left.

923
00:34:25,466 --> 00:34:27,366
-Twelve? Already?
-Already?

924
00:34:27,433 --> 00:34:28,333
It's going by so fast.

925
00:34:28,400 --> 00:34:30,533
The time limit doesn't seem enough.

926
00:34:30,733 --> 00:34:32,600
MINCED GARLIC

927
00:34:32,900 --> 00:34:34,166
BUTTER

928
00:34:34,500 --> 00:34:35,500
OATMEAL

929
00:34:35,733 --> 00:34:36,900
MILK

930
00:34:36,966 --> 00:34:38,900
He said he'd make risotto with oatmeal.

931
00:34:38,966 --> 00:34:40,900
You can do that?

932
00:34:41,666 --> 00:34:43,533
It may not happen.

933
00:34:43,600 --> 00:34:46,533
-With that, it'll turn into porridge.
-It'll become porridge.

934
00:34:46,600 --> 00:34:49,133
You want that bite when you eat risotto,

935
00:34:49,199 --> 00:34:50,900
but that'll just turn into porridge.

936
00:34:50,966 --> 00:34:53,233
He says that dish will
turn out like porridge.

937
00:34:53,300 --> 00:34:55,466
-That was Poong's prediction.
-Yes.

938
00:34:55,533 --> 00:34:57,233
-I'm sure he has a way.
-I'm sure.

939
00:34:57,300 --> 00:34:59,266
He's the winner of <i>Culinary Class Wars.</i>

940
00:34:59,333 --> 00:35:00,900
-Don't forget that.
-I was the winner?

941
00:35:01,133 --> 00:35:02,333
TOFU

942
00:35:02,566 --> 00:35:03,733
GRIND EVERYTHING TOGETHER

943
00:35:03,800 --> 00:35:05,200
MULTITASKING

944
00:35:05,266 --> 00:35:08,133
Oatmeal doesn't have too much starch.
So that means…

945
00:35:08,200 --> 00:35:10,266
Poong says
it'll turn out like porridge, not rice.

946
00:35:10,333 --> 00:35:12,900
-It'll 100% be like that.
-Really?

947
00:35:12,966 --> 00:35:16,066
-The winner of <i>CCW</i> doesn't know that?
-What's wrong?

948
00:35:16,133 --> 00:35:17,533
I'm worried.

949
00:35:17,600 --> 00:35:19,433
-I can do this.
-You can?

950
00:35:20,000 --> 00:35:21,433
THE WINNER OF CCW IS CONFIDENT!

951
00:35:21,666 --> 00:35:24,033
REMOVING THE MUSHROOM STEMS

952
00:35:24,100 --> 00:35:26,066
In the button mushrooms…

953
00:35:26,133 --> 00:35:28,533
It's like that Chinese dish.

954
00:35:28,600 --> 00:35:31,166
-The one with shiitake.
-Yes, stuffed mushrooms.

955
00:35:31,233 --> 00:35:32,500
That's shrimp, right?

956
00:35:32,566 --> 00:35:34,666
-He mixed shrimp and tofu.
-Really?

957
00:35:34,733 --> 00:35:38,233
-He stuffed them.
-You're grilling, not steaming?

958
00:35:38,300 --> 00:35:40,733
I'll cook them in the pan
and then once more on the fire.

959
00:35:40,800 --> 00:35:42,000
No grease?

960
00:35:42,066 --> 00:35:43,733
-With grease.
-With oil.

961
00:35:45,666 --> 00:35:47,000
A SUDDEN FIRE SHOW

962
00:35:47,066 --> 00:35:48,300
He set it on fire.

963
00:35:48,366 --> 00:35:50,100
No, I doubt it.

964
00:35:50,166 --> 00:35:53,033
-Did you intentionally set it on fire?
-It just caught on fire.

965
00:35:53,100 --> 00:35:53,933
BLOW!

966
00:35:54,000 --> 00:35:56,733
-I don't think so. It's too hot.
-Stay calm.

967
00:35:56,800 --> 00:35:59,166
That's exactly what happened 12 years ago!

968
00:35:59,400 --> 00:36:00,666
ON FIRE EVERY TIME HE COMES

969
00:36:00,733 --> 00:36:02,233
We saw that 12 years ago.

970
00:36:02,300 --> 00:36:04,000
Why does this always happen when I'm here?

971
00:36:04,066 --> 00:36:06,033
-Pull them out, Sung-jun.
-Put a lid on it.

972
00:36:06,100 --> 00:36:07,766
-Pull them out.
-Put a lid on it.

