1209
00:44:47,566 --> 00:44:49,166
He used oatmeal.

1210
00:44:49,233 --> 00:44:51,100
-Risotto.
-Does it taste like risotto?

1211
00:44:51,166 --> 00:44:52,433
He said tomatoes will add a kick.

1212
00:44:52,500 --> 00:44:54,766
-The texture must be different.
-He doesn't like oatmeal.

1213
00:44:54,833 --> 00:44:57,200
Do the tomatoes add something?

1214
00:44:57,266 --> 00:44:59,033
-His face.
-Oatmeal is still oatmeal.

1215
00:45:00,066 --> 00:45:01,600
Oatmeal is still oatmeal.

1216
00:45:01,833 --> 00:45:03,300
QUESTIONING

1217
00:45:03,366 --> 00:45:04,633
Oatmeal can't become risotto.

1218
00:45:04,700 --> 00:45:06,766
ACCUSING LOOK

1219
00:45:06,833 --> 00:45:09,733
Hey, don't make that face at the chef!

1220
00:45:09,800 --> 00:45:12,200
What's that face?
After all, he's still a chef.

1221
00:45:12,266 --> 00:45:14,266
-It should be okay.
-He tried his best.

1222
00:45:14,333 --> 00:45:17,600
-I don't think you can…
-But you know…

1223
00:45:17,666 --> 00:45:18,600
…call this risotto.

1224
00:45:18,666 --> 00:45:20,166
-It's not.
-I mean the texture.

1225
00:45:20,233 --> 00:45:23,566
But it's unbelievable
that he made this with oatmeal.

1226
00:45:23,633 --> 00:45:24,666
I see.

1227
00:45:24,733 --> 00:45:26,600
I can also detect
a bit of broccoli at the end,

1228
00:45:26,666 --> 00:45:29,166
and it tastes really good
when it hits me.

1229
00:45:29,233 --> 00:45:30,900
-And the tomatoes?
-You need the tomatoes.

1230
00:45:30,966 --> 00:45:34,366
The flavor by itself isn't strong,
but it's perfect with the tomatoes.

1231
00:45:34,433 --> 00:45:35,833
-I see.
-Right?

1232
00:45:35,900 --> 00:45:37,900
-What did you do with them?
-Tomatoes?

1233
00:45:37,966 --> 00:45:41,400
<i>I mixed them with olive oil,</i>
<i>salt, ground pepper, and sugar,</i>

1234
00:45:41,466 --> 00:45:43,966
<i>then cooked them for ten minutes</i>
<i>in the air fryer.</i>

1235
00:45:44,033 --> 00:45:46,233
The flavor gets maximized as they dry.

1236
00:45:46,300 --> 00:45:48,866
-And becomes this strong?
-Yes.

1237
00:45:48,933 --> 00:45:49,766
I see.

1238
00:45:49,833 --> 00:45:51,366
It's like sun-dried tomatoes.

1239
00:45:51,433 --> 00:45:55,733
It's like rice with kimchi.
It improves the flavor so much.

1240
00:45:55,800 --> 00:45:57,233
It also counters the richness.

1241
00:45:57,300 --> 00:46:00,133
It includes more tofu than I expected.

1242
00:46:00,200 --> 00:46:03,333
-Sorry? Yes, tofu. I used soft tofu.
-There's lots of tofu.

1243
00:46:03,400 --> 00:46:05,166
It tastes like beans,

1244
00:46:05,233 --> 00:46:08,133
-so I can definitely feel the healthiness.
-It's healthy.

1245
00:46:08,200 --> 00:46:11,333
The face that he just made
was the face Sang-hwa would love.

1246
00:46:11,400 --> 00:46:12,333
Right?

1247
00:46:12,400 --> 00:46:15,066
-Sang-hwa would love this.
-She would.

1248
00:46:15,866 --> 00:46:19,566
The grimmer his face gets,
the happier she will be.

1249
00:46:19,633 --> 00:46:21,533
I was curious about this one.

1250
00:46:21,600 --> 00:46:23,533
-Broccoli and American cheese.
-Yes.

1251
00:46:24,900 --> 00:46:26,800
-Broccoli…
-Whoa.

1252
00:46:26,866 --> 00:46:29,466
-Do you like the broccoli chips?
-Amazing.

1253
00:46:29,533 --> 00:46:32,366
-But you don't like broccoli.
-I can eat this every day.

1254
00:46:33,533 --> 00:46:37,133
I don't particularly like broccoli,
but I can enjoy this very much.

1255
00:46:37,200 --> 00:46:39,166
Is it because of the cheese?

1256
00:46:39,233 --> 00:46:40,833
Right. The cheese powder.

1257
00:46:40,900 --> 00:46:42,066
-The powder.
-Parmesan cheese powder.

1258
00:46:42,133 --> 00:46:44,066
-Parmesan cheese powder.
-It was at the bottom.

1259
00:46:44,133 --> 00:46:47,100
-This combination works really well.
-It does.

1260
00:46:47,166 --> 00:46:49,133
With dishes like this,

1261
00:46:49,200 --> 00:46:51,733
-I could lose weight while feeling happy.
-You're right.

1262
00:46:51,800 --> 00:46:53,533
It'll definitely help me lose weight.

1263
00:46:53,600 --> 00:46:55,966
What about it would Sang-hwa like?

1264
00:46:56,033 --> 00:46:59,033
-First of all, it's green.
-It's green.

1265
00:46:59,100 --> 00:47:01,166
Also, it's my favorite, risotto.

1266
00:47:01,233 --> 00:47:03,366
I like how he made it taste like that.

1267
00:47:04,333 --> 00:47:07,333
-I love it.
-He loves it.

1268
00:47:07,400 --> 00:47:09,666
Next, please try Chef Ho-young's dish.

1269
00:47:09,733 --> 00:47:12,600
Chef Ho-young's Sang-hwa-licious Roll.

1270
00:47:12,666 --> 00:47:16,233
ROLLS WITH TSUKUNE AND VARIOUS VEGGIES

1271
00:47:17,033 --> 00:47:21,533
WITH JAPANESE PICKLED PLUM DIP
THAT "SOMEONE" HELPED WITH

1272
00:47:22,400 --> 00:47:26,300
CHEF JUNG HO-YOUNG'S SANG-HWA-LICIOUS ROLL

1273
00:47:26,366 --> 00:47:28,366
-Try the small pieces first.
-The cut piece.

1274
00:47:28,433 --> 00:47:29,266
Just like this?

1275
00:47:29,333 --> 00:47:30,633
-No sauce?
-No.

1276
00:47:30,700 --> 00:47:33,400
-Try it as is first, and then as you like.
-Try it as is.

1277
00:47:33,466 --> 00:47:35,133
A BITE WITHOUT THE SAUCE

1278
00:47:37,366 --> 00:47:38,766
IMMEDIATE RESPONSE

1279
00:47:38,833 --> 00:47:40,100
He's liking it.

1280
00:47:40,600 --> 00:47:42,500
That must be good.

1281
00:47:43,233 --> 00:47:44,766
It's good.

1282
00:47:44,833 --> 00:47:46,933
RIGHT UP HIS ALLEY

1283
00:47:47,000 --> 00:47:48,166
The <i>tsukune</i> is so good.

1284
00:47:48,233 --> 00:47:50,333
-It's healthy too, right?
-It must be.

1285
00:47:50,400 --> 00:47:53,933
Rather than having just veggies,
it's healthier to add some protein.

1286
00:47:54,000 --> 00:47:56,166
-And veggies are boring.
-Also,

1287
00:47:56,233 --> 00:47:59,700
it already tastes nice
even without the sauce.

1288
00:47:59,766 --> 00:48:03,533
Japanese pickled plums
help with your digestion too,

1289
00:48:03,600 --> 00:48:05,566
so try some and enjoy the sourness.

1290
00:48:05,633 --> 00:48:08,333
-I love <i>umeboshi</i> too.
-I see.

1291
00:48:08,400 --> 00:48:09,533
I love them so much.

1292
00:48:09,600 --> 00:48:11,400
-Try it with the sauce.
-Okay.

1293
00:48:11,466 --> 00:48:13,666
YUM

1294
00:48:14,233 --> 00:48:15,733
He makes it look so good.

1295
00:48:15,800 --> 00:48:18,866
It was really salty and sour to me.

1296
00:48:18,933 --> 00:48:20,866
He must like it a lot.

1297
00:48:21,633 --> 00:48:23,000
-With his dishes…
-The sauce.

1298
00:48:23,066 --> 00:48:24,400
A thumbs-up for the sauce.

1299
00:48:24,466 --> 00:48:26,000
-Sung-ju said it was too salty.
-Yes.

1300
00:48:26,066 --> 00:48:29,000
It's not salty at all.
What are you talking about? It's so good.

1301
00:48:29,066 --> 00:48:30,766
-I did see him add sugar later.
-It's not salty.

1302
00:48:30,833 --> 00:48:33,633
<i>I added the boiled rice water</i>
<i>and cooking wine mix</i>

1303
00:48:33,700 --> 00:48:36,133
and diluted the sauce
to make it less salty.

1304
00:48:36,200 --> 00:48:37,833
I tasted it before all that.

1305
00:48:37,900 --> 00:48:40,166
I really love <i>umeboshi</i>.

1306
00:48:40,233 --> 00:48:41,766
Japanese people would love this.

1307
00:48:41,833 --> 00:48:43,233
They pair so well together.

1308
00:48:43,300 --> 00:48:46,666
I didn't think spring rolls
would be compatible

1309
00:48:46,733 --> 00:48:48,533
with <i>umeboshi</i> sauce.

1310
00:48:48,600 --> 00:48:49,700
How can I put this?

1311
00:48:49,766 --> 00:48:52,100
-Tangy. Tangy and light.
-Tangy.

1312
00:48:52,166 --> 00:48:53,966
-It's like that.
-The sauce?

1313
00:48:54,033 --> 00:48:56,766
-It adds a lot to the dish.
-I see.

1314
00:48:56,833 --> 00:48:58,433
And the whole roll.

1315
00:48:58,500 --> 00:49:00,733
-Dip it in the sauce.
-Don't hold back.

1316
00:49:01,033 --> 00:49:02,266
TORTUROUS

1317
00:49:02,333 --> 00:49:04,233
-One more.
-Dip it right in.

1318
00:49:04,300 --> 00:49:05,966
-Goodness.
-Have a bite.

1319
00:49:06,033 --> 00:49:06,966
Bite on it.

1320
00:49:07,533 --> 00:49:09,433
It's stuffed with veggies,
so it won't be salty.

1321
00:49:09,500 --> 00:49:10,633
It can't be.

1322
00:49:10,700 --> 00:49:12,466
-It's not salty, right?
-No.

1323
00:49:13,133 --> 00:49:14,900
You want some, don't you?

1324
00:49:14,966 --> 00:49:16,600
He keeps making low grunts. "Mmm."

1325
00:49:16,666 --> 00:49:20,200
I just became curious
as I watched him eat.

1326
00:49:20,266 --> 00:49:24,066
<i>Tsukune</i>, cucumber,
and what's this? Carrot.

1327
00:49:24,133 --> 00:49:26,433
They were all julienned
except for the <i>tsukune</i>, right?

1328
00:49:26,500 --> 00:49:29,966
-I love the mix in my mouth.
-Because they were julienned.

1329
00:49:30,033 --> 00:49:31,133
Will Sang-hwa like it?

1330
00:49:31,200 --> 00:49:33,333
No, I think I'll like it. It's so good.

1331
00:49:34,300 --> 00:49:35,633
It's surprisingly good.

1332
00:49:35,700 --> 00:49:37,466
He was supposed to make
something Sang-hwa would love.

1333
00:49:37,533 --> 00:49:39,266
If you like it, she'll hate it. Right?

1334
00:49:39,333 --> 00:49:41,566
But she'd love it more

1335
00:49:41,633 --> 00:49:43,800
-because it has lots of veggies.
-There are veggies.

1336
00:49:44,700 --> 00:49:45,600
And low in calories.

1337
00:49:45,666 --> 00:49:47,366
Isn't the sauce too strong?

1338
00:49:47,433 --> 00:49:49,733
I like it more because it's strong.

1339
00:49:49,800 --> 00:49:51,533
Wouldn't Sang-hwa think it's too strong?

1340
00:49:51,600 --> 00:49:53,933
-She can't eat this at all.
-What?

1341
00:49:54,000 --> 00:49:55,466
SANG-HWA CAN'T EAT THE SAUCE?

1342
00:49:55,533 --> 00:49:56,833
She doesn't like <i>umeboshi</i>?

1343
00:49:56,900 --> 00:49:58,766
That's why I served it separately.

1344
00:49:59,766 --> 00:50:01,333
SO THAT THE COUPLE CAN BOTH ENJOY IT

1345
00:50:01,400 --> 00:50:02,666
She won't have to eat it.

1346
00:50:02,733 --> 00:50:05,166
-That was a fast recovery.
-She doesn't have to eat the sauce.

1347
00:50:05,233 --> 00:50:07,100
Nice save.

1348
00:50:07,166 --> 00:50:08,833
-You were almost in trouble.
-He's good.

1349
00:50:08,900 --> 00:50:10,666
Sang-hwa doesn't have to eat it.

1350
00:50:10,733 --> 00:50:13,666
But the roll itself is good
even without the sauce.

1351
00:50:13,733 --> 00:50:16,100
Where's the seasoning? In the meat?

1352
00:50:16,166 --> 00:50:19,966
I seasoned the meat
with <i>tsuyu</i> and <i>yuja</i> pepper paste.

1353
00:50:20,033 --> 00:50:21,366
I see, he used <i>yuzu kosho</i>.

1354
00:50:21,433 --> 00:50:23,833
It's so good. That explains the tanginess.

1355
00:50:23,900 --> 00:50:26,200
Didn't you salt
and season the veggies too?

1356
00:50:26,266 --> 00:50:28,400
I salted the carrot,

1357
00:50:28,466 --> 00:50:32,433
<i>then seasoned it</i>
<i>with honey, vinegar, and mustard.</i>

1358
00:50:32,500 --> 00:50:35,533
-It's so good.
-So you seasoned everything.

1359
00:50:35,600 --> 00:50:39,533
I loved the crunchiness
of the vegetables and everything.

1360
00:50:39,600 --> 00:50:41,666
Now, please try

1361
00:50:41,733 --> 00:50:44,433
Chef Sung-jun's Sang-hwa-licious Risotto.

1362
00:50:45,533 --> 00:50:48,466
-It has the texture of risotto.
-It does.

1363
00:50:48,533 --> 00:50:51,033
EVERYTHING IN ONE BITE

1364
00:50:51,100 --> 00:50:54,633
-It's so good.
-He worked hard to turn oatmeal into this.

1365
00:50:55,266 --> 00:50:56,833
It's easy to eat.

1366
00:50:56,900 --> 00:50:58,533
-It goes down easily.
-It does.

1367
00:50:58,600 --> 00:50:59,600
Yes.

1368
00:50:59,666 --> 00:51:01,966
-It's healthy yet filling.
-And filling.

1369
00:51:02,033 --> 00:51:03,966
This oatmeal

1370
00:51:04,033 --> 00:51:07,766
maintained its chewy texture,
so as someone who loves <i>tteok</i>,

1371
00:51:07,833 --> 00:51:09,600
I would eat this instead of that

1372
00:51:09,666 --> 00:51:12,500
when I'm looking to lose weight.
It's nice and chewy.

1373
00:51:12,566 --> 00:51:13,566
Instead of <i>tteok</i>?

1374
00:51:13,633 --> 00:51:16,700
-I have a feeling Nam-no won't like it.
-Nam-no.

1375
00:51:16,766 --> 00:51:18,900
Personally speaking,

1376
00:51:18,966 --> 00:51:20,533
I do not like this kind of food.

1377
00:51:20,600 --> 00:51:23,000
-Something healthy.
-That means he did a good job.

1378
00:51:23,066 --> 00:51:24,900
But the tofu

1379
00:51:24,966 --> 00:51:27,133
<i>keeps the dish nicely balanced,</i>

1380
00:51:27,200 --> 00:51:30,166
<i>along with the salty and savory cheese.</i>

1381
00:51:30,233 --> 00:51:32,333
I actually enjoyed it,

1382
00:51:32,400 --> 00:51:34,166
even though I despise dishes like these.

1383
00:51:34,233 --> 00:51:37,166
Even those who hate this kind of food
can still enjoy it.

1384
00:51:37,233 --> 00:51:38,300
-Yes.
-Okay.

1385
00:51:38,366 --> 00:51:40,200
Next, Chef Ho-young's dish.

1386
00:51:40,266 --> 00:51:41,833
Sang-hwa-licious Roll.

1387
00:51:42,866 --> 00:51:44,600
Sang-hwa-licious Roll.

1388
00:51:45,033 --> 00:51:46,833
SMOTHERED WITH SAUCE

1389
00:51:47,300 --> 00:51:49,533
TAKES A BITE

1390
00:51:50,466 --> 00:51:52,466
Woo-rim tries just the sauce.

1391
00:51:52,533 --> 00:51:54,766
Isn't the <i>umeboshi</i> sauce fantastic?

1392
00:51:54,833 --> 00:51:56,100
Right?

1393
00:51:56,166 --> 00:51:58,500
-It's good.
-This is good. It's so good.

1394
00:51:58,566 --> 00:52:00,833
When we travel to Southeast Asia,

1395
00:52:00,900 --> 00:52:02,366
we can take yoga lessons, right?

1396
00:52:02,433 --> 00:52:04,000
So we did a session with an instructor,

1397
00:52:04,066 --> 00:52:06,400
a healthy and luxurious lesson.

1398
00:52:06,466 --> 00:52:08,433
After the lesson,

1399
00:52:08,500 --> 00:52:11,000
the instructor turned out to be Japanese.
That's the vibe I got.

1400
00:52:11,066 --> 00:52:13,000
SOUTHEAST ASIA MEETS JAPAN

1401
00:52:13,066 --> 00:52:16,666
Spring rolls are usually served
with chili sauce or Sriracha.

1402
00:52:16,733 --> 00:52:17,966
-Yes.
-The <i>umeboshi</i> sauce

1403
00:52:18,033 --> 00:52:20,600
<i>eliminates the greasiness</i>

1404
00:52:20,666 --> 00:52:22,533
<i>and brings out the veggie flavors.</i>

1405
00:52:22,600 --> 00:52:25,400
-A bite of protein, carbs, and fat.
-It's perfect.

1406
00:52:25,466 --> 00:52:28,700
And now, you must make your choice.

1407
00:52:28,766 --> 00:52:31,133
A Dish Lee Sang-hwa Would Love.

1408
00:52:31,200 --> 00:52:33,133
<i>Press one for Kwon Sung-jun,</i>

1409
00:52:33,200 --> 00:52:34,766
<i>and two for Jung Ho-young.</i>

1410
00:52:35,533 --> 00:52:37,933
Make your decision and press the button!

1411
00:52:39,133 --> 00:52:40,500
Press one!

1412
00:52:40,566 --> 00:52:42,100
-I did.
-You did?

1413
00:52:42,166 --> 00:52:43,733
-He did.
-Already?

1414
00:52:43,800 --> 00:52:47,266
Let's find out who he chose. Show us!

1415
00:52:47,333 --> 00:52:51,400
A Dish Lee Sang-hwa Would Love,
someone who loves healthy food.

1416
00:52:51,466 --> 00:52:53,300
I feel bad.

1417
00:52:53,366 --> 00:52:54,266
Right?

1418
00:52:54,333 --> 00:52:56,600
Will Sung-jun win a star

1419
00:52:56,666 --> 00:52:59,166
after a fun cook-off with his master?

1420
00:52:59,233 --> 00:53:03,066
Or will Chef Ho-young beat Sung-jun

1421
00:53:03,133 --> 00:53:05,366
and rise into the top rankings?

1422
00:53:05,933 --> 00:53:07,133
Who did Kangnam choose?

1423
00:53:07,200 --> 00:53:08,800
Who is it?

1424
00:53:09,366 --> 00:53:11,500
Which dish would Sang-hwa like more?

1425
00:53:11,566 --> 00:53:13,200
Which one was for Sang-hwa?

1426
00:53:13,266 --> 00:53:14,366
Who's the winner?

1427
00:53:14,433 --> 00:53:15,933
KWON SUNG-JUN WINS

1428
00:53:16,266 --> 00:53:17,100
SANG-HWA-LICIOUS RISOTTO WINS

1429
00:53:17,166 --> 00:53:19,066
Kwon Sung-jun wins!

1430
00:53:19,133 --> 00:53:21,900
A STUDENT TURNED MASTER
OR BITING THE HAND THAT FED HIM

1431
00:53:21,966 --> 00:53:23,300
It's Sung-jun.

1432
00:53:23,366 --> 00:53:25,633
Sang-hwa would love this so much.

1433
00:53:25,700 --> 00:53:27,900
-The risotto
-Made with oatmeal.

1434
00:53:27,966 --> 00:53:30,233
and broccoli, which I should be eating,

1435
00:53:30,300 --> 00:53:32,266
even surprised me too.

1436
00:53:32,333 --> 00:53:36,500
-What she and I would both love is that.
-The risotto.

1437
00:53:36,566 --> 00:53:38,433
-And about the roll…
-Yes.

1438
00:53:39,000 --> 00:53:41,833
I really love making those rolls

1439
00:53:41,900 --> 00:53:44,066
-and could have 20 at a time.
-I knew it.

1440
00:53:44,133 --> 00:53:46,800
That's why Sang-hwa hates it
when I eat them.

1441
00:53:47,733 --> 00:53:49,866
-Why are you telling him that now?
-She hates it.

1442
00:53:49,933 --> 00:53:52,933
She says if I eat that much,
even healthy food can make me fat.

1443
00:53:53,000 --> 00:53:54,800
I often got scolded for that.

1444
00:53:54,866 --> 00:53:58,000
Sang-hwa hates it when I eat spring rolls

1445
00:53:58,066 --> 00:53:59,500
and <i>umeboshi</i>.

1446
00:53:59,566 --> 00:54:01,333
You made everything she hates.

1447
00:54:02,400 --> 00:54:03,966
I should've gone on the next round.

1448
00:54:04,033 --> 00:54:05,933
He lost because it was too good.

1449
00:54:06,000 --> 00:54:07,633
And he won because it was bad.

1450
00:54:08,866 --> 00:54:10,200
He won because it was bad.

1451
00:54:10,266 --> 00:54:12,633
Food for weight loss
must be filling, even if it's not good.

1452
00:54:12,700 --> 00:54:14,266
Yes, and it was really filling.

1453
00:54:14,333 --> 00:54:16,933
-It has to stop you from eating too much.
-Yes.

1454
00:54:17,000 --> 00:54:19,000
Sung-jun beats his master

1455
00:54:19,066 --> 00:54:22,066
and wins a star today.
Let's hear from him.

1456
00:54:22,133 --> 00:54:24,566
It's all thanks to my master,
and his great teachings.

1457
00:54:24,633 --> 00:54:26,600
He never taught you anything!

1458
00:54:26,666 --> 00:54:28,100
Which master?

1459
00:54:28,166 --> 00:54:31,133
-I learned a lot from Master Ho-young…
-He's a funny character.

1460
00:54:31,200 --> 00:54:33,166
…so I'll now find another one.

1461
00:54:33,233 --> 00:54:34,566
He's leaving him.

1462
00:54:34,633 --> 00:54:37,033
FAREWELL TO THE MASTER

1463
00:54:37,633 --> 00:54:39,633
Ho-young never
taught him anything, though.

1464
00:54:39,700 --> 00:54:42,266
-He's a funny one.
-Please put a star on Sung-jun!

1465
00:54:42,333 --> 00:54:43,500
SUNG-JUN'S THIRD STAR

1466
00:54:43,566 --> 00:54:44,733
Congratulations!

1467
00:54:44,800 --> 00:54:46,233
-Congratulations.
-Thank you.

1468
00:54:46,300 --> 00:54:47,666
He takes his third star!

1469
00:54:47,733 --> 00:54:51,766
<i>This is the second round of the cook-off</i>
<i>with Kangnam's ingredients.</i>

1470
00:54:51,833 --> 00:54:55,866
Webtoon Artist Kim Poong,
who's ready to turn his back on Sang-hwa,

1471
00:54:55,933 --> 00:54:59,166
versus Chef Park Eun-yeong,
who's determined

1472
00:54:59,233 --> 00:55:01,066
not to lose against Kim Poong as of today.

1473
00:55:01,133 --> 00:55:04,033
Poong has been doing well lately,
winning twice in a row.

1474
00:55:04,100 --> 00:55:07,566
But he ended up coming across
a huge stumbling block called Eun-yeong.

1475
00:55:07,633 --> 00:55:09,333
-A stumbling block?
-Here's Eun-yeong record.

1476
00:55:09,400 --> 00:55:11,400
In the previous season and this season,

1477
00:55:11,466 --> 00:55:13,300
she won all five rounds against him.

1478
00:55:13,366 --> 00:55:14,500
You don't mix well with her.

1479
00:55:14,566 --> 00:55:16,966
-She's strong against Poong.
-She has never lost to him.

1480
00:55:17,033 --> 00:55:18,800
-That's crazy.
-He's an easy prey.

1481
00:55:18,866 --> 00:55:22,166
Poong, why are you
especially weak against Eun-yeong?

1482
00:55:22,233 --> 00:55:24,900
It's like when people say
that two people aren't compatible.

1483
00:55:24,966 --> 00:55:27,333
-Something about us doesn't click.
-No?

1484
00:55:27,400 --> 00:55:30,000
-Should I hold an exorcism ritual?
-Maybe.

1485
00:55:30,066 --> 00:55:32,233
But you've won all five times
against Chef Nam-no.

1486
00:55:33,200 --> 00:55:35,600
But you lost all five times
against Eun-yeong.

1487
00:55:35,666 --> 00:55:38,933
How do we explain this?
Is it really about compatibility?

1488
00:55:39,000 --> 00:55:42,266
Are you weak against a Chinese chef
because your foundation is there too?

1489
00:55:42,333 --> 00:55:44,966
Will that affect things?
I think that might be it.

1490
00:55:45,033 --> 00:55:46,466
-Even he doesn't know.
-Something's up.

1491
00:55:46,533 --> 00:55:47,766
She said something like this.

1492
00:55:47,833 --> 00:55:49,566
"Just imagining losing to Poong,

1493
00:55:49,633 --> 00:55:52,033
who has no roots, makes me enraged."

1494
00:55:52,100 --> 00:55:54,366
-What does that make me?
-Poong has no roots,

1495
00:55:54,433 --> 00:55:56,433
but you do?

1496
00:55:56,500 --> 00:55:59,400
He's someone who often makes Chinese food.

1497
00:55:59,966 --> 00:56:03,433
-But frankly, I was born and bred in it.
-You were.

1498
00:56:03,500 --> 00:56:04,933
You have a long pedigree.

1499
00:56:05,000 --> 00:56:06,466
But Poong right here

1500
00:56:06,533 --> 00:56:08,700
has no roots and is from the streets.

1501
00:56:09,066 --> 00:56:10,333
PLEBEIAN POONG

1502
00:56:10,400 --> 00:56:11,566
-Yes.
-From the streets.

1503
00:56:11,633 --> 00:56:12,833
STREET FOOD EXPERT?

1504
00:56:12,900 --> 00:56:14,800
"From the streets." That's rough.

1505
00:56:15,066 --> 00:56:16,666
SEVERE CLASS DIFFERENCE

1506
00:56:16,733 --> 00:56:17,966
You'll be making

1507
00:56:18,033 --> 00:56:19,600
A Dish Lee Sang-hwa Would Hate.

1508
00:56:19,666 --> 00:56:21,800
-Meaning, something Kangnam will like.
-That's right.

1509
00:56:21,866 --> 00:56:23,533
Do you feel confident about this?

1510
00:56:23,600 --> 00:56:27,233
Well, Kangnam and I have done
some programs together

1511
00:56:27,300 --> 00:56:28,900
when he hit 100 kg.

1512
00:56:28,966 --> 00:56:31,466
I probably contributed about 5 kg of that.

1513
00:56:31,533 --> 00:56:32,966
No. No way.

1514
00:56:33,033 --> 00:56:34,633
-It's ten.
-It's ten?

1515
00:56:34,700 --> 00:56:36,933
-He fed me so much.
-You have a fair share.

1516
00:56:37,000 --> 00:56:39,200
-I do.
-He fed me a lot.

1517
00:56:39,266 --> 00:56:42,533
I should avoid Sang-hwa
as much as possible.

1518
00:56:42,600 --> 00:56:45,166
She probably doesn't like me even now.

1519
00:56:45,233 --> 00:56:46,633
So I'll brace myself

1520
00:56:46,700 --> 00:56:48,900
and feed Kangnam until he's full today.

1521
00:56:49,066 --> 00:56:50,633
READY TO EAT

1522
00:56:51,066 --> 00:56:53,333
WEBTOON ARTIST POONG'S INGREDIENTS: SQUID,
GREEN ONION KIMCHI, SHABU-SHABU BEEF

1523
00:56:53,400 --> 00:56:55,633
SHRIMP, OYSTER SAUCE, CHOCOLATE SYRUP,
CHICKEN STOCK, CHOCOLATE COOKIE CHEESECAKE

1524
00:56:55,700 --> 00:56:57,833
The dish I'm making today is

1525
00:56:57,900 --> 00:57:00,500
Where Poong Goes, Kangnam Follows.

1526
00:57:00,566 --> 00:57:03,166
-Where Poong Goes, Kangnam Follows.
-Where Poong Goes, Kangnam Follows.

1527
00:57:03,233 --> 00:57:05,000
-Not following a friend to Gangnam?
-No.

1528
00:57:05,066 --> 00:57:08,533
Today, I will challenge her face-to-face
and make Chinese food.

1529
00:57:09,500 --> 00:57:10,700
-Really?
-Yes.

1530
00:57:10,766 --> 00:57:12,133
Are you sure?

1531
00:57:12,200 --> 00:57:14,033
The epitome of Chinese food,

1532
00:57:14,100 --> 00:57:15,600
<i>-jjamppong.</i>
<i>-Jjamppong.</i>

1533
00:57:15,666 --> 00:57:18,433
But of course, I'll add my own kick.

1534
00:57:18,500 --> 00:57:20,033
It's green onion kimchi <i>jjamppong</i>.

1535
00:57:20,100 --> 00:57:21,966
-Green onion kimchi <i>jjamppong?</i>
-Green onion kimchi?

1536
00:57:22,033 --> 00:57:23,000
Green onion kimchi <i>jjamppong?</i>

1537
00:57:23,066 --> 00:57:26,333
-It sounds good. I'm already drooling.
-Already?

1538
00:57:26,400 --> 00:57:28,166
-My mouth is watering.
-I'll make <i>jjamppong</i>

1539
00:57:28,233 --> 00:57:31,333
-and the noodles will be from scratch.
-From scratch?

1540
00:57:31,400 --> 00:57:33,633
-I'll make fresh noodles.
-You won't have time.

1541
00:57:33,700 --> 00:57:36,300
But they'll be
thicker and thinner than usual.

1542
00:57:36,366 --> 00:57:37,500
-What?
-Right.

1543
00:57:37,566 --> 00:57:39,200
What do you mean, "thicker and thinner?"

1544
00:57:39,266 --> 00:57:41,066
-Thicker lengthwise…
-Wider?

1545
00:57:41,133 --> 00:57:43,300
-Wider. Wider and thinner.
-Wider and thinner.

1546
00:57:43,366 --> 00:57:45,900
-I'll make wide and thin noodles.
-He's stuttering.

1547
00:57:45,966 --> 00:57:47,333
He must feel pressured.

1548
00:57:47,400 --> 00:57:50,266
It'll be a bit like <i>sujebi</i> too.

1549
00:57:50,333 --> 00:57:52,200
So a <i>jjamppong</i> like that.

1550
00:57:52,266 --> 00:57:53,533
He has a sweet tooth.

1551
00:57:53,600 --> 00:57:55,000
I love sweet things.

1552
00:57:55,066 --> 00:57:56,533
I know he does,

1553
00:57:56,600 --> 00:57:57,900
but he can't eat it at home.

1554
00:57:57,966 --> 00:58:00,566
-You're right.
-You can have as much as you want here,

1555
00:58:00,633 --> 00:58:02,633
so I'll make chocolate <i>jjajangmyeon</i>.

1556
00:58:02,966 --> 00:58:04,133
CHOCOLATE JJAJANGMYEON?

1557
00:58:04,200 --> 00:58:06,166
-What's chocolate <i>jjajangmyeon?</i>
-You're making both?

1558
00:58:06,233 --> 00:58:07,433
I'm making <i>jjamjja-myeon.</i>

1559
00:58:07,500 --> 00:58:09,500
You said you'd make
authentic Chinese food.

1560
00:58:09,566 --> 00:58:11,266
<i>Jjamjja-myeon</i> is Korean-Chinese food.

1561
00:58:11,333 --> 00:58:12,533
You said it was chocolate.

1562
00:58:12,600 --> 00:58:14,166
Chocolate <i>jjajangmyeon</i>.

1563
00:58:14,233 --> 00:58:16,633
-Chocolate <i>jjajangmyeon?</i>
-Made with chocolate?

1564
00:58:16,700 --> 00:58:18,100
I'll make that.

1565
00:58:18,166 --> 00:58:20,066
You're unable to keep a straight face.

1566
00:58:20,133 --> 00:58:22,066
I'm really excited for it.

1567
00:58:22,133 --> 00:58:23,566
I'm getting a little worried.

1568
00:58:23,633 --> 00:58:25,366
Yes, it doesn't sound easy.

1569
00:58:25,833 --> 00:58:28,066
CHEF EUN-YEONG'S INGREDIENTS:
SQUID, KING OYSTER MUSHROOM

1570
00:58:28,133 --> 00:58:30,366
SHIITAKE, SHRIMP,
THIN PORK BELLY, OYSTER SAUCE

1571
00:58:30,433 --> 00:58:33,400
Up against him is Chef Eun-yeong.
What will you be making?

1572
00:58:33,466 --> 00:58:35,133
The name of my dish is this.

1573
00:58:35,200 --> 00:58:36,633
This Is Kangnam Style.

1574
00:58:36,700 --> 00:58:38,300
-It's not.
-This Is Kangnam Style?

1575
00:58:38,366 --> 00:58:39,833
-This Is Kangnam Style.
-How shocking.

1576
00:58:39,900 --> 00:58:42,066
-What's it like?
-She's bold.

1577
00:58:42,133 --> 00:58:43,933
I prepared something in Kangnam's style,

1578
00:58:44,000 --> 00:58:47,466
something Sang-hwa would hate,
something that'll make her faint.

1579
00:58:47,533 --> 00:58:49,200
There's a Chinese dish called chow mein.

1580
00:58:49,266 --> 00:58:50,500
-Chow mein.
-Chow mein.

1581
00:58:50,566 --> 00:58:52,433
It means fried noodles.

1582
00:58:52,500 --> 00:58:55,266
I'll use <i>ramyeon</i> noodles today,
which were already deep-fried,

1583
00:58:55,333 --> 00:58:57,400
and I'll deep-fry them again
to make chow mein.

1584
00:58:57,466 --> 00:58:59,300
-It sounds like hell.
-And also,

1585
00:58:59,366 --> 00:59:01,333
I must make it look perfect too.

1586
00:59:01,400 --> 00:59:03,100
When you go to Japan or China,

1587
00:59:03,166 --> 00:59:06,166
you'll see chopsticks fixed up in the air
wrapped with noodles.

1588
00:59:06,233 --> 00:59:07,633
-Yes.
-I'll make that

1589
00:59:07,700 --> 00:59:09,666
so that Sang-hwa will hate the look of it

1590
00:59:09,733 --> 00:59:11,533
as well as the taste of it,

1591
00:59:11,600 --> 00:59:12,766
and make her shudder.

1592
00:59:12,833 --> 00:59:14,800
I think she really will hate that.

1593
00:59:14,866 --> 00:59:16,500
She'll be shocked to watch it on TV.

1594
00:59:16,700 --> 00:59:18,133
SORRY, SANG-HWA

1595
00:59:18,200 --> 00:59:19,566
But will Kangnam like it?

1596
00:59:19,633 --> 00:59:22,266
I'm deep-frying <i>ramyeon</i> noodles,

1597
00:59:22,333 --> 00:59:24,000
so it will ruin his health.

1598
00:59:24,266 --> 00:59:25,700
IS THAT A CURSE OR HER CONFIDENCE?

1599
00:59:25,766 --> 00:59:28,333
You might as well just curse him.

1600
00:59:28,400 --> 00:59:29,766
That's so funny.

1601
00:59:29,833 --> 00:59:31,766
-You rarely eat like that now.
-It's been a while.

1602
00:59:31,833 --> 00:59:33,766
I'll bring his fatty liver back!

1603
00:59:34,033 --> 00:59:35,733
USING THE FATTY LIVER CARD

1604
00:59:35,800 --> 00:59:39,433
So they need to make Kangnam sick
to win a star?

1605
00:59:39,500 --> 00:59:43,200
Sang-hwa thinks
I'll only order healthy dishes here.

1606
00:59:43,266 --> 00:59:44,966
-I see.
-Your orders?

1607
00:59:45,033 --> 00:59:46,766
Once she watches this episode,

1608
00:59:46,833 --> 00:59:48,433
she will be extremely annoyed.

1609
00:59:48,733 --> 00:59:50,666
TREMBLING

1610
00:59:50,733 --> 00:59:52,466
I'm risking my life to eat today.

1611
00:59:52,533 --> 00:59:54,700
Sang-hwa, if you're watching now,

1612
00:59:54,766 --> 00:59:56,633
you can probably turn off the TV.

1613
00:59:56,700 --> 00:59:58,233
-She should.
-Yes.

1614
00:59:58,300 --> 00:59:59,733
All right, now.

1615
00:59:59,800 --> 01:00:01,700
Let's begin the round for Kangnam,

1616
01:00:01,766 --> 01:00:05,400
A Dish Lee Sang-hwa Would Hate.

1617
01:00:05,466 --> 01:00:08,300
All ready to make Sang-hwa riled up,

1618
01:00:08,366 --> 01:00:11,566
the troublemaker of the show,
Webtoon Artist Kim Poong.

1619
01:00:11,633 --> 01:00:15,500
All ready to make
both Sang-hwa and Poong faint,

1620
01:00:15,566 --> 01:00:19,100
the crazy one of the show,
Chef Park Eun-yeong.

1621
01:00:19,166 --> 01:00:23,333
Which one of them will receive
a complaint from Sang-hwa?

1622
01:00:23,400 --> 01:00:27,000
Let the 15-minute cook-off begin!

1623
01:00:27,900 --> 01:00:29,466
AUTHENTIC CHINESE FOOD
VS. BOOTLEG CHINESE FOOD

1624
01:00:30,133 --> 01:00:32,033
It's fine as long as Kangnam likes it.

1625
01:00:32,100 --> 01:00:34,266
-Just him.
-Something Sang-hwa would hate.

1626
01:00:34,333 --> 01:00:36,433
Eun-yeong pulls out the noodles.

1627
01:00:36,500 --> 01:00:38,100
She's using three bags of noodles.

1628
01:00:38,166 --> 01:00:39,633
-No, four.
-Why so many?

1629
01:00:39,700 --> 01:00:42,800
-Right? I wonder.
-Will she deep-fry those?

1630
01:00:42,866 --> 01:00:44,233
She'll probably boil them first.

1631
01:00:44,300 --> 01:00:46,800
-Boil and then fry.
-Boil first.

1632
01:00:46,866 --> 01:00:47,700
TIMER

1633
01:00:47,766 --> 01:00:51,833
Eun-yeong will use the <i>ramyeon</i> noodles,

1634
01:00:51,900 --> 01:00:53,866
but Poong will make them from scratch.

1635
01:00:54,866 --> 01:00:56,800
-What's that in the machine?
-The dough.

1636
01:00:56,866 --> 01:00:57,900
-The dough.
-The dough.

1637
01:00:57,966 --> 01:00:59,100
It looks good.

1638
01:00:59,166 --> 01:01:01,600
-That's too little.
-You can make dough with that?

1639
01:01:01,666 --> 01:01:02,500
It's wet dough.

1640
01:01:03,300 --> 01:01:05,033
Green onion oil. No, Poong's chili oil.

1641
01:01:05,100 --> 01:01:07,133
-Is it green onion oil?
-Poong's chili oil.

1642
01:01:07,200 --> 01:01:09,633
As always, Poong makes chili oil again.

1643
01:01:09,700 --> 01:01:12,800
-That's a lot of red pepper powder.
-Is it too much?

1644
01:01:12,866 --> 01:01:13,966
Do you enjoy spicy food?

1645
01:01:14,033 --> 01:01:15,266
-I like it.
-He likes it.

1646
01:01:15,333 --> 01:01:17,533
-It has to be nicely spicy.
-Nicely spicy.

1647
01:01:17,600 --> 01:01:20,200
After Sang-hwa watches this episode,

1648
01:01:20,266 --> 01:01:21,800
you'll have to run 15 km every day.

1649
01:01:21,866 --> 01:01:23,533
More like 20 km.

1650
01:01:24,266 --> 01:01:27,100
She might tie you to her car
and drag you around.

1651
01:01:27,166 --> 01:01:30,566
-It's that serious.
-Yes, she'll do that after you eat those.

1652
01:01:31,833 --> 01:01:33,700
GREEN ONION

1653
01:01:34,433 --> 01:01:36,366
Eun-yeong preps the ingredients first.

1654
01:01:36,433 --> 01:01:38,533
Squid. Is that like <i>jjamppong</i> too?

1655
01:01:38,600 --> 01:01:40,066
KING OYSTER MUSHROOM, SHIITAKE

1656
01:01:40,133 --> 01:01:43,300
-Chef Eun-yeong chops so quickly.
-She does.

1657
01:01:43,366 --> 01:01:44,966
The authentic chef is different.

1658
01:01:45,033 --> 01:01:49,300
In Chinese cuisine, chefs prep first
and then move on to cooking.

1659
01:01:49,366 --> 01:01:52,200
-Whoa.
-Whoa.

1660
01:01:52,266 --> 01:01:53,866
The angle is inconsistent.

1661
01:01:54,600 --> 01:01:57,100
-The shapes are not even at all.
-No.

1662
01:01:58,266 --> 01:01:59,100
It sounds normal, but…

1663
01:01:59,166 --> 01:02:01,266
Cut off the tip, will you?

1664
01:02:01,333 --> 01:02:02,700
Cut it off?

1665
01:02:02,766 --> 01:02:03,600
TURNS

1666
01:02:03,866 --> 01:02:04,700
CHOPPED OFF!

1667
01:02:04,766 --> 01:02:06,900
No! The opposite side!

1668
01:02:07,500 --> 01:02:10,100
How did he make the sizes all different?

1669
01:02:10,166 --> 01:02:11,633
To add different textures.

1670
01:02:11,700 --> 01:02:13,400
They weren't separated,
so he's using his hand.

1671
01:02:13,466 --> 01:02:14,833
REMOVING THE TIP WITH HIS HAND

1672
01:02:14,900 --> 01:02:18,066
He separated the pieces
with his hand. Come on.

1673
01:02:19,200 --> 01:02:21,000
COOK THE NOODLES ONLY FOR 2 MINUTES

1674
01:02:21,066 --> 01:02:23,133
Chef Eun-yeong is almost done
prepping the ingredients.

1675
01:02:23,200 --> 01:02:24,166
She's so fast.

1676
01:02:24,233 --> 01:02:26,833
She finished prepping
in just 2 minutes and 30 seconds.

1677
01:02:26,900 --> 01:02:29,333
She's making noodles,
so she'd better finish first.

1678
01:02:29,400 --> 01:02:30,300
-Yes.
-Right.

1679
01:02:30,366 --> 01:02:34,833
She washes the cooked <i>ramyeon</i> noodles
in cold water.

1680
01:02:34,900 --> 01:02:36,933
THE NIMBLE HANDS OF CHEF & MY FRIDGE!

1681
01:02:37,000 --> 01:02:38,633
-And she strains them.
-She's really fast.

1682
01:02:38,700 --> 01:02:40,900
-She'll deep-fry those later.
-She's fast.

1683
01:02:40,966 --> 01:02:42,933
Above all, I love the portion.

1684
01:02:43,000 --> 01:02:44,100
She used four bags.

1685
01:02:44,166 --> 01:02:46,566
-What's that powder? Starch?
-Starch.

1686
01:02:46,633 --> 01:02:47,666
To deep-fry them.

1687
01:02:47,733 --> 01:02:50,700
She grabs some. She'll deep-fry them.

1688
01:02:50,766 --> 01:02:52,600
That wok has a built-in strainer.

1689
01:02:52,666 --> 01:02:54,533
-That's a thing?
-Chow mein.

1690
01:02:54,600 --> 01:02:56,266
Chili oil is done.

1691
01:02:56,333 --> 01:02:58,866
-Did the chili oil turn out well?
-Look at the color.

1692
01:02:59,166 --> 01:03:01,466
LOOKS MORE INTENSE THAN USUAL

1693
01:03:01,533 --> 01:03:03,000
-Next, green onion kimchi.
-Green onion kimchi.

1694
01:03:03,066 --> 01:03:05,000
-He gets the kimchi.
-Are you washing those?

1695
01:03:05,066 --> 01:03:07,066
-Yes.
-I see.

1696
01:03:07,133 --> 01:03:08,966
The red pepper powder

1697
01:03:09,033 --> 01:03:11,766
-will make it taste stale.
-He's making <i>jjamppong</i>.

1698
01:03:11,833 --> 01:03:14,500
It's been four minutes already.

1699
01:03:14,566 --> 01:03:16,500
-Time flies.
-He has to hurry.

1700
01:03:16,566 --> 01:03:17,900
What are you making, Poong?

1701
01:03:17,966 --> 01:03:21,033
-It's <i>jjamppong</i>.
-The ingredients for <i>jjamppong?</i>

1702
01:03:21,100 --> 01:03:23,166
I have to make <i>jjamppong</i> broth now.

1703
01:03:24,100 --> 01:03:25,466
She's deep-frying it.

1704
01:03:25,533 --> 01:03:26,633
That looks good.

1705
01:03:26,700 --> 01:03:28,500
She's deep-frying the noodles?

1706
01:03:28,566 --> 01:03:29,633
She's frying them.

1707
01:03:30,566 --> 01:03:33,033
-And she wraps the chopsticks with them.
-What's she doing?

1708
01:03:33,100 --> 01:03:34,866
-She's making that shape.
-What's she doing?

1709
01:03:34,933 --> 01:03:35,833
For the shape?

1710
01:03:35,900 --> 01:03:39,800
It's like the fake food display you see
with the chopsticks in the air.

1711
01:03:39,866 --> 01:03:41,600
-I see.
-Like those noodles.

1712
01:03:41,666 --> 01:03:42,866
-What?
-She'll fry it like that?

1713
01:03:42,933 --> 01:03:44,833
If she deep-fries that,
will the shape stay?

1714
01:03:44,900 --> 01:03:46,700
Someone will have to hold it.

1715
01:03:46,766 --> 01:03:48,433
We need someone to do that.

1716
01:03:48,500 --> 01:03:50,066
-"Someone."
-You.

1717
01:03:50,133 --> 01:03:51,633
-Me?
-Nam-no.

1718
01:03:51,700 --> 01:03:54,233
-He didn't know.
-Nam-no didn't know,

1719
01:03:54,300 --> 01:03:55,566
but he has to hold it.

1720
01:03:55,633 --> 01:03:57,833
-Why didn't she tell me?
-Can you deep-fry it?

1721
01:03:57,900 --> 01:03:59,133
I didn't know.

1722
01:03:59,200 --> 01:04:00,933
GET UP IF YOU THINK IT'S YOU
DO I HAVE TO SAY IT?

1723
01:04:01,000 --> 01:04:02,700
It got deep-fried.

1724
01:04:02,766 --> 01:04:03,866
What now?

1725
01:04:03,933 --> 01:04:05,233
-Come here.
-Here?

1726
01:04:05,300 --> 01:04:07,200
-Next to you? Or here?
-Stand there.

1727
01:04:07,266 --> 01:04:08,833
-Stand there? Here?
-Hold this.

1728
01:04:08,900 --> 01:04:11,333
-If it fails, it's over.
-A little lower.

1729
01:04:11,400 --> 01:04:14,800
-Will she pour hot oil over that?
-She'll pour the oil?

1730
01:04:14,866 --> 01:04:16,666
She'll pour it over the top?

1731
01:04:16,733 --> 01:04:18,666
Then will the shape stay fixed?

1732
01:04:18,733 --> 01:04:22,366
-It'll stay, thanks to the starch.
-Yes, she's coating it with more starch.

1733
01:04:22,433 --> 01:04:24,966
-This is a first.
-So this is how you do it.

1734
01:04:25,033 --> 01:04:26,733
Will it work?

1735
01:04:26,800 --> 01:04:28,433
-Will it?
-I've never done it either.

1736
01:04:28,500 --> 01:04:30,766
-She'll pour oil over it.
-I'm dying to see it.

1737
01:04:30,833 --> 01:04:33,033
-Will it work? Watch your hand.
-She's pouring.

1738
01:04:33,100 --> 01:04:34,600
OIL SHOWER!

1739
01:04:34,666 --> 01:04:35,966
-It won't work.
-Just like that?

1740
01:04:36,533 --> 01:04:39,166
A little lower. The chopsticks.

1741
01:04:39,233 --> 01:04:41,466
-It won't be easy.
-The height is important.

1742
01:04:41,533 --> 01:04:42,833
You won't pour it on me, right?

1743
01:04:42,900 --> 01:04:43,933
Deal with it.

1744
01:04:44,000 --> 01:04:45,600
-Nam-no backs up.
-Hang in there!

1745
01:04:45,666 --> 01:04:48,333
-Even if she fries my hand?
-Yes, hang in there.

1746
01:04:48,400 --> 01:04:51,666
HE JUST HAS TO HANG IN THERE?

1747
01:04:51,733 --> 01:04:53,766
-Just hang in there.
-Hang in there.

1748
01:04:53,833 --> 01:04:55,033
-Hang in there.
-She pours oil on it.

1749
01:04:55,100 --> 01:04:56,866
Eight minutes and twenty seconds.

1750
01:04:56,933 --> 01:05:00,300
-It's an emergency.
-To the center.

1751
01:05:00,366 --> 01:05:02,233
-I don't think it'll work.
-No. Is it okay?

1752
01:05:02,300 --> 01:05:04,133
Stick something in the middle.

1753
01:05:04,200 --> 01:05:06,266
-Wait, it's working.
-It is?

1754
01:05:06,333 --> 01:05:08,266
-It's working?
-It is.

1755
01:05:08,333 --> 01:05:10,300
-She's almost there.
-Right?

1756
01:05:10,366 --> 01:05:12,766
It's standing on its own!

1757
01:05:12,833 --> 01:05:15,866
-Try letting it go.
-Let it go?

1758
01:05:15,933 --> 01:05:16,933
Let it go.

1759
01:05:17,900 --> 01:05:19,366
-Let it go.
-Let it go?

1760
01:05:19,433 --> 01:05:21,700
-Let it go. Whoa!
-It worked. It's in the air.

1761
01:05:21,766 --> 01:05:23,533
Hold it for a little longer.

1762
01:05:23,600 --> 01:05:25,066
-Hang in there.
-Lift it up a little.

1763
01:05:25,133 --> 01:05:27,000
-Okay.
-Lift it.

1764
01:05:28,100 --> 01:05:30,166
-Lift it.
-It's staying in the air.

1765
01:05:30,233 --> 01:05:31,300
-He let it go.
-Wait.

1766
01:05:31,866 --> 01:05:34,333
Eun-yeong captures everyone's attention.

1767
01:05:34,400 --> 01:05:35,933
-It's staying, right?
-It's in the air.

1768
01:05:36,000 --> 01:05:37,366
-It worked.
-Yes.

1769
01:05:39,500 --> 01:05:41,600
She made the shape!

1770
01:05:41,666 --> 01:05:43,466
She made it!

1771
01:05:43,533 --> 01:05:44,400
Okay.

1772
01:05:45,533 --> 01:05:48,066
Meanwhile, Poong makes <i>jjamppong</i> broth.

1773
01:05:48,133 --> 01:05:49,500
It's an emergency.

1774
01:05:49,566 --> 01:05:51,300
Minced garlic?

1775
01:05:51,366 --> 01:05:54,500
That <i>jjamppong</i> soup looks really spicy.

1776
01:05:54,566 --> 01:05:55,933
Squid.

1777
01:05:56,000 --> 01:05:57,600
Squid and shrimp.

1778
01:05:57,666 --> 01:05:59,500
-That's <i>jjamppong </i>soup, right?
-Yes.

1779
01:05:59,566 --> 01:06:01,700
It looks like <i>jjamppong</i>.

1780
01:06:01,766 --> 01:06:04,200
Bootleg versus authentic Chinese food.

1781
01:06:04,433 --> 01:06:06,433
WHAT ABOUT THE AUTHENTIC ONE?

1782
01:06:06,500 --> 01:06:09,833
PARBOIL SHIITAKE AND SQUID
FOR AN AUTHENTIC RECIPE

1783
01:06:09,900 --> 01:06:11,733
WIPING DOWN

1784
01:06:11,800 --> 01:06:14,866
I can't believe
Poong is cleaning the counter.

1785
01:06:14,933 --> 01:06:16,366
He has to make the noodles now.

1786
01:06:16,433 --> 01:06:18,433
-To make the noodles.
-For the noodles.

1787
01:06:18,500 --> 01:06:22,233
If he fails, he'll have to
open a bag of <i>ramyeon </i>too.

1788
01:06:22,300 --> 01:06:24,833
-Or he can just turn it into <i>sujebi.</i>
<i>-Sujebi?</i>

1789
01:06:24,900 --> 01:06:26,900
-The whole dough?
-<i>Sujebi</i>.

1790
01:06:26,966 --> 01:06:29,833
Poong wants to make fresh noodles himself.

1791
01:06:29,900 --> 01:06:31,600
The portion is too small.

1792
01:06:31,666 --> 01:06:33,500
-Noodles take a while.
-Even chefs have

1793
01:06:33,566 --> 01:06:36,400
-a tough time pulling noodles.
-Yes.

1794
01:06:36,466 --> 01:06:38,300
That's not enough dough.

1795
01:06:38,366 --> 01:06:39,833
Seven minutes left!

1796
01:06:41,733 --> 01:06:43,033
Poong, your chili oil.

1797
01:06:43,100 --> 01:06:44,333
-What?
-Do you have leftovers?

1798
01:06:44,400 --> 01:06:46,366
My chili oil? Why?

1799
01:06:46,433 --> 01:06:48,133
-You won't need all this, right?
-Why?

1800
01:06:48,200 --> 01:06:50,533
"Do you have leftover chili oil?"

1801
01:06:50,600 --> 01:06:52,433
-Do you need all of this? Just this much.
-Why?

1802
01:06:52,500 --> 01:06:55,000
-Wait, what are you doing?
-I need it to make the stir-fry delicious.

1803
01:06:55,066 --> 01:06:56,766
Wait, what is this?

1804
01:06:56,833 --> 01:06:59,100
Eun-yeong nonchalantly steals his oil.

1805
01:06:59,166 --> 01:07:01,133
Can she steal what I made?

1806
01:07:01,566 --> 01:07:04,233
1 YEAR AND 7 MONTHS AGO

1807
01:07:04,300 --> 01:07:06,266
SHE GOT HER OIL STOLEN IN HER DEBUT ROUND

1808
01:07:06,466 --> 01:07:07,566
USING STOLEN OIL

1809
01:07:07,633 --> 01:07:08,766
TO MAKE POONG'S CHILI OIL!

1810
01:07:09,033 --> 01:07:10,866
I WILL NOT FORGET THIS!

1811
01:07:10,933 --> 01:07:12,933
I'm sorry. That must've been yours.

1812
01:07:13,000 --> 01:07:15,000
-Let me use some.
-She steals the oil.

1813
01:07:15,700 --> 01:07:16,666
-What is this?
-Sorry.

1814
01:07:16,733 --> 01:07:19,133
-Sorry. I'm sorry.
-Why did you take my oil?

1815
01:07:19,200 --> 01:07:20,500
DUMBFOUNDED

1816
01:07:20,566 --> 01:07:22,166
-What was that?
-I'm sorry.

1817
01:07:22,233 --> 01:07:23,066
I'm sorry.

1818
01:07:24,700 --> 01:07:25,633
I'm sorry.

1819
01:07:25,700 --> 01:07:27,200
WHAT'S WITH THAT ANNOYING TONE?

1820
01:07:27,266 --> 01:07:28,200
That's so annoying!

1821
01:07:28,266 --> 01:07:29,700
What's she doing?

1822
01:07:29,766 --> 01:07:31,333
He was busy rolling the dough.

1823
01:07:31,400 --> 01:07:33,266
-What was that?
-He couldn't even fight back.

1824
01:07:33,333 --> 01:07:35,666
That was so annoying.

1825
01:07:35,733 --> 01:07:37,366
-You only have six minutes.
-Wait.

1826
01:07:37,433 --> 01:07:38,533
Six minutes.

1827
01:07:38,600 --> 01:07:40,866
-Unbelievable.
-Minced garlic.

1828
01:07:40,933 --> 01:07:42,366
-What? What do you need?
-What?

1829
01:07:42,433 --> 01:07:44,333
Poong keeps getting robbed.

1830
01:07:44,400 --> 01:07:45,233
GRABS A DISH

1831
01:07:45,300 --> 01:07:46,800
-Let me use some minced garlic.
-What?

1832
01:07:46,866 --> 01:07:48,566
-Thanks.
-She goes back!

1833
01:07:48,633 --> 01:07:49,533
She steals again!

1834
01:07:49,800 --> 01:07:53,766
DOES ANYBODY KNOW WHAT THAT TONE IS?

1835
01:07:53,833 --> 01:07:56,233
-She steals again.
-What did she take?

1836
01:07:56,300 --> 01:07:57,433
-Garlic.
-What was it?

1837
01:07:57,500 --> 01:07:59,766
-What was it?
-It was garlic.

1838
01:07:59,833 --> 01:08:01,066
Is that her new concept?

1839
01:08:01,133 --> 01:08:03,666
-"I'm sorry."
-She keeps stealing.

1840
01:08:03,733 --> 01:08:06,166
You can't hate her
with that bubbly tone, can you?

1841
01:08:06,233 --> 01:08:09,200
-She's so brazen.
-Very bright.

1842
01:08:09,266 --> 01:08:10,500
"Do you have leftover oil?"

1843
01:08:10,566 --> 01:08:11,400
You can't hate her.

1844
01:08:11,466 --> 01:08:13,633
Man, that was annoying.

1845
01:08:14,200 --> 01:08:17,366
Whoa, the noodles look great.

1846
01:08:17,433 --> 01:08:21,500
-The wide yet thin noodles.
-Just like that?

1847
01:08:21,566 --> 01:08:23,000
-Wide and thin noodles.
-It looks like

1848
01:08:23,066 --> 01:08:25,166
-pappardelle pasta.
-It looks good.

1849
01:08:25,233 --> 01:08:26,766
He did a great job.

1850
01:08:26,833 --> 01:08:31,033
-There are wide noodles in Japan too.
-Yes, it's called <i>kishimen</i>.

1851
01:08:31,100 --> 01:08:33,800
-The noodles look like that.
-Yes.

1852
01:08:33,866 --> 01:08:37,433
Wider noodles require saltier broth.

1853
01:08:37,500 --> 01:08:40,133
-I remember that.
-It does look a bit salty.

1854
01:08:40,200 --> 01:08:41,633
Five minutes left!

1855
01:08:41,700 --> 01:08:42,566
-Five minutes.
-Jung-hwan!

1856
01:08:42,633 --> 01:08:44,166
-It's your turn!
-Yes.

1857
01:08:44,233 --> 01:08:46,200
Wait, five minutes?

1858
01:08:46,266 --> 01:08:47,166
This is bad.

1859
01:08:47,233 --> 01:08:48,733
Put the noodles in first.

1860
01:08:48,800 --> 01:08:52,399
-This isn't good.
-Poong doesn't seem to have enough time.

1861
01:08:52,466 --> 01:08:55,633
-It needs to boil hard.
-You have to cook the noodles. Poong.

1862
01:08:55,700 --> 01:08:59,300
The soup looks good…
You put green onion kimchi in here.

1863
01:08:59,366 --> 01:09:00,700
-Jung-hwan!
-Yes?

1864
01:09:00,766 --> 01:09:03,733
Can you try the <i>jjamppong</i> soup?

1865
01:09:03,800 --> 01:09:05,233
-I should, right?
-You're making more?

1866
01:09:05,300 --> 01:09:06,300
Wait, what?

1867
01:09:06,366 --> 01:09:07,500
It's too late now.

1868
01:09:07,566 --> 01:09:09,033
I told you the portion was too small.

1869
01:09:09,100 --> 01:09:12,033
-I hope he makes the noodles.
-I'll try the <i>jjamppong</i> soup.

1870
01:09:12,100 --> 01:09:14,933
I've never had soup
made with green onion kimchi.

1871
01:09:15,000 --> 01:09:17,033
-Is it fully seasoned?
-Yes.

1872
01:09:17,100 --> 01:09:18,600
You won't have enough time.

1873
01:09:19,166 --> 01:09:20,666
What's the soup like?

1874
01:09:20,733 --> 01:09:22,733
Can Kim Poong

1875
01:09:22,800 --> 01:09:25,233
break his jinx this time?

1876
01:09:25,300 --> 01:09:26,600
Can he beat Eun-yeong?

1877
01:09:26,666 --> 01:09:28,100
Sang-hwa will probably

1878
01:09:28,166 --> 01:09:29,800
slap him across the face.

1879
01:09:30,700 --> 01:09:31,566
Good.

1880
01:09:31,633 --> 01:09:33,066
It's so intense,

1881
01:09:33,133 --> 01:09:35,733
-but still a little bland.
-Is it a bit bland?

1882
01:09:35,800 --> 01:09:36,866
OK!

1883
01:09:36,933 --> 01:09:39,200
It's still a little bland.

1884
01:09:39,266 --> 01:09:40,800
-Four minutes.
-A bit bland.

1885
01:09:40,866 --> 01:09:42,133
Shouldn't you cook the noodles?

1886
01:09:42,200 --> 01:09:44,433
-I have to.
-You have to.

1887
01:09:44,500 --> 01:09:48,966
-I'll just put them in here.
-No! That'll turn into <i>kal-guksu!</i>

1888
01:09:49,033 --> 01:09:50,866
Don't you have to
boil them in water first?

1889
01:09:50,933 --> 01:09:53,966
It'll turn out like <i>kal-guksu</i>
because of the flour.

1890
01:09:54,033 --> 01:09:56,833
It's intentional.
I want to thicken the soup.

1891
01:09:56,900 --> 01:09:58,566
You have to make <i>jjajangmyeon</i> too.

1892
01:09:58,633 --> 01:10:00,066
Yes, he said he'd make <i>jjajangmyeon</i>.

1893
01:10:00,133 --> 01:10:01,833
That's why he's making the noodles again.

1894
01:10:01,900 --> 01:10:04,300
These noodles are standing up.
It's fascinating.

1895
01:10:04,366 --> 01:10:06,200
-They're standing.
-I see.

1896
01:10:06,700 --> 01:10:08,400
SQUID, KING OYSTER MUSHROOM, SHIITAKE

1897
01:10:09,033 --> 01:10:12,266
4. STIR-FRY PORK BELLY, SQUID, MUSHROOMS,
AND POUR WATER TO MAKE BROTH

1898
01:10:13,966 --> 01:10:15,400
RAMYEON SOUP BASE FOR AUTHENTIC CHINESE?

1899
01:10:15,466 --> 01:10:16,300
OYSTER SAUCE

1900
01:10:16,366 --> 01:10:17,200
GROUND PEPPER

1901
01:10:18,066 --> 01:10:20,566
How will you use that soup?

1902
01:10:20,633 --> 01:10:23,366
-He'll pour it on the noodles and eat it.
-On the noodles.

1903
01:10:23,433 --> 01:10:25,500
-Three minutes?
-Three minutes left.

1904
01:10:25,566 --> 01:10:28,700
-You got this!
-Just wing it!

1905
01:10:28,766 --> 01:10:30,033
Chocolate <i>jjajangmyeon!</i>

1906
01:10:30,100 --> 01:10:32,233
-<i>Jjajangmyeon?</i>
-He's running out of time.

1907
01:10:32,300 --> 01:10:33,266
Just wing it.

1908
01:10:33,333 --> 01:10:34,733
Poong feels rushed!

1909
01:10:34,800 --> 01:10:37,500
-You have to do this too.
-What are you doing?

1910
01:10:37,566 --> 01:10:39,266
POONG IS FIGHTING THE DOUGH

1911
01:10:39,333 --> 01:10:40,966
It's not getting cut.

1912
01:10:41,033 --> 01:10:42,600
I can see the lines.

1913
01:10:42,666 --> 01:10:44,966
RIPPING IT APART WITH A KNIFE!

1914
01:10:45,033 --> 01:10:47,433
-That's enough.
-Just throw them in!

1915
01:10:47,500 --> 01:10:48,700
-Put them in.
-Fry them.

1916
01:10:48,766 --> 01:10:52,133
Fry them! Just fry them!

1917
01:10:52,200 --> 01:10:54,400
-The oil seems too hot.
-It's too hot.

1918
01:10:54,466 --> 01:10:57,800
Wait, these aren't <i>jjajangmyeon</i>.
These look like puffed grain snacks!

1919
01:10:57,866 --> 01:10:59,166
Dumpling skins.

1920
01:10:59,233 --> 01:11:01,400
Will he deep-fry those
and serve them with chocolate?

1921
01:11:01,466 --> 01:11:03,366
-He'll make it look like <i>jjajangmyeon.</i>
-Yes.

1922
01:11:03,433 --> 01:11:04,566
-It's burning!
-Heat off!

1923
01:11:04,633 --> 01:11:07,166
-Get them out.
-The strainer.

1924
01:11:07,233 --> 01:11:10,100
-You can turn the heat off. Put it down.
-The strainer.

1925
01:11:10,166 --> 01:11:12,133
-Two minutes left.
-Yes.

1926
01:11:12,200 --> 01:11:13,666
Let me try her broth.

1927
01:11:14,300 --> 01:11:15,633
It's the sauce for the noodles.

1928
01:11:15,700 --> 01:11:17,500
The broth for the noodles!

1929
01:11:17,566 --> 01:11:20,433
Does it taste like
it'll make Sang-hwa faint?

1930
01:11:21,500 --> 01:11:23,300
She will faint!

1931
01:11:23,366 --> 01:11:24,600
-It must be good.
-It must be.

1932
01:11:24,666 --> 01:11:27,433
It's rich, delicious, and strong.

1933
01:11:27,500 --> 01:11:28,866
I can feel my veins getting clogged.

1934
01:11:30,333 --> 01:11:31,466
OH GOSH

1935
01:11:31,866 --> 01:11:34,766
CHOCOLATE SYRUP

1936
01:11:35,133 --> 01:11:36,900
CHOCOLATE COOKIE CHEESECAKE

1937
01:11:37,833 --> 01:11:38,966
SANG-HWA WILL SLAP HIS BACK

1938
01:11:39,033 --> 01:11:39,933
He grinds the chocolate.

1939
01:11:40,000 --> 01:11:42,066
It's not just that. That and cheesecake.

1940
01:11:42,133 --> 01:11:44,100
-He added cake.
-He added cheesecake too.

1941
01:11:44,166 --> 01:11:46,966
-I see.
-It's chocolate cake and syrup.

1942
01:11:47,033 --> 01:11:49,266
-Is that oil?
-Did you pour more oil on them?

1943
01:11:49,333 --> 01:11:50,666
This is done.

1944
01:11:50,733 --> 01:11:53,466
-She made the shape.
-1 minute and 30 seconds!

1945
01:11:53,533 --> 01:11:56,666
Poong, you'll burn this. It's burnt!

1946
01:11:56,733 --> 01:11:59,066
-It's burnt.
-One of them is burnt.

1947
01:11:59,133 --> 01:12:00,700
-It's burnt!
-It'll be served with chocolate,

1948
01:12:00,766 --> 01:12:02,766
so it may not be noticeable.

1949
01:12:02,833 --> 01:12:04,700
But I saw it already.

1950
01:12:04,766 --> 01:12:06,666
Time is almost up.

1951
01:12:06,733 --> 01:12:08,333
GIVES UP ON THE BURNT ONE

1952
01:12:08,400 --> 01:12:11,700
-One minute.
-He blots off the grease.

1953
01:12:11,766 --> 01:12:14,400
-Taste the <i>jjamppong</i>.
-One minute left!

1954
01:12:14,466 --> 01:12:16,733
IT'S THIS BOWL

1955
01:12:16,800 --> 01:12:18,700
The bowl! It's that bowl!

1956
01:12:18,766 --> 01:12:20,600
-<i>Jjamjja-myeon </i>bowl.
-What is that?

1957
01:12:20,666 --> 01:12:22,200
Chocolate.

1958
01:12:23,166 --> 01:12:26,133
-Fifty seconds.
-Taste the <i>jjamppong</i>.

1959
01:12:26,200 --> 01:12:27,566
-It's still hot!
-It's almost over.

1960
01:12:27,633 --> 01:12:29,233
All right. One minute.

1961
01:12:29,300 --> 01:12:32,000
THE BROTH TO POUR OVER THE NOODLES

1962
01:12:32,466 --> 01:12:33,300
GRABS A SPOON

1963
01:12:34,366 --> 01:12:35,200
Thanks, Poong.

1964
01:12:36,533 --> 01:12:38,700
Hey, what's she doing?

1965
01:12:38,766 --> 01:12:41,700
-What's with her?
-She said, "Thanks, Poong."

1966
01:12:41,766 --> 01:12:43,266
That tone is so funny.

1967
01:12:43,333 --> 01:12:44,833
"Thanks, Poong."

1968
01:12:44,900 --> 01:12:46,266
At least she thanked him.

1969
01:12:46,333 --> 01:12:49,433
-She can save time and not make the oil.
-I don't have to make it.

1970
01:12:49,966 --> 01:12:52,033
POONG DOESN'T EVEN HAVE TIME TO FIGHT BACK

1971
01:12:52,100 --> 01:12:53,966
Dang it.

1972
01:12:54,033 --> 01:12:55,566
-Twenty-seven seconds.
-Look at that soup.

1973
01:12:55,633 --> 01:12:58,633
-You have time.
-He spilled everything.

1974
01:12:58,700 --> 01:13:00,533
POURING THE CHOCOLATE SAUCE!

1975
01:13:01,100 --> 01:13:02,300
Ring the bell.

1976
01:13:04,033 --> 01:13:05,100
EUN-YEONG FINISHES

1977
01:13:05,366 --> 01:13:07,266
NICE TO MEET YOU, CHOW MEIN

1978
01:13:07,333 --> 01:13:10,666
-Eun-yeong is done. 15 seconds!
-The soup!

1979
01:13:10,733 --> 01:13:13,466
-You need the soup!
-Don't let them mix.

1980
01:13:13,533 --> 01:13:15,866
-Ten. Nine. Eight.
-If you do, you ruin both!

1981
01:13:15,933 --> 01:13:16,866
Seven.

1982
01:13:16,933 --> 01:13:17,800
-Six.
-Six.

1983
01:13:17,866 --> 01:13:19,700
-Five. Four.
-Five. Four.

1984
01:13:19,766 --> 01:13:21,900
-Three. Two.
-Three. Two.

1985
01:13:21,966 --> 01:13:23,000
-One.
-One.

1986
01:13:23,066 --> 01:13:26,100
-Time's up!
-Time's up!

1987
01:13:26,700 --> 01:13:28,233
That's the time.

1988
01:13:28,300 --> 01:13:29,466
HE SOMEHOW FINISHED BOTH!

1989
01:13:29,533 --> 01:13:31,666
-Kim Poong finishes.
-He's done.

1990
01:13:31,733 --> 01:13:33,166
KIM POONG'S DISH IS FINISHED

1991
01:13:33,733 --> 01:13:35,133
Look at these.

1992
01:13:35,200 --> 01:13:36,633
"Thank you."

1993
01:13:36,700 --> 01:13:39,366
-They came out in decent shape.
-It looks like <i>jjajang</i> sauce.

1994
01:13:39,433 --> 01:13:41,733
-That's amazing.
-It's crazy.

1995
01:13:41,800 --> 01:13:43,566
Chinese cuisine is such a wonder.

1996
01:13:44,133 --> 01:13:45,500
LET'S JUST ENJOY THIS MOMENT

1997
01:13:45,566 --> 01:13:47,166
How did you two do this?

1998
01:13:47,233 --> 01:13:49,733
-Whoa.
-Both chefs finished making

1999
01:13:49,800 --> 01:13:52,666
A Dish Lee Sang-hwa Would Hate.

2000
01:13:52,733 --> 01:13:55,133
I tasted them both, right?

2001
01:13:55,200 --> 01:13:56,400
-I tell you this.
-Yes?

2002
01:13:56,466 --> 01:13:57,500
Kangnam.

2003
01:13:57,566 --> 01:13:59,800
-You're done staying in shape.
-I am?

2004
01:13:59,866 --> 01:14:03,400
-You'd better be careful.
-Yes, even just looking at it.

2005
01:14:03,466 --> 01:14:04,966
Today is a special day.

2006
01:14:05,033 --> 01:14:07,733
-I haven't had a day like this.
-Right?

2007
01:14:07,800 --> 01:14:10,833
-Chef Eun-yeong stole some chili oil.
-Thanks.

2008
01:14:10,900 --> 01:14:12,800
But you can't hate her.

2009
01:14:12,866 --> 01:14:16,033
She was like,
"Do you have oil? I'm taking some!"

2010
01:14:16,100 --> 01:14:18,566
-"Thanks!"
-"Thanks!"

2011
01:14:18,633 --> 01:14:19,900
Thanks for the chili oil.

2012
01:14:19,966 --> 01:14:21,300
I'll teach you how to make <i>jjamppong</i>.

2013
01:14:22,466 --> 01:14:24,233
That'll turn into her catchphrase.

2014
01:14:24,300 --> 01:14:25,666
-"Thanks."
-"Thanks."

2015
01:14:25,733 --> 01:14:29,233
Please try Chef Eun-yeong's dish first.

2016
01:14:29,300 --> 01:14:30,933
This Is Kangnam Style.

2017
01:14:31,000 --> 01:14:33,333
DEEP-FRIED CHOW MEIN IN A CRAZY SHAPE

2018
01:14:33,866 --> 01:14:35,700
AND SCORCHED RICE SOUP-STYLE BROTH

2019
01:14:35,766 --> 01:14:36,600
WITH POONG'S CHILI OIL

2020
01:14:37,700 --> 01:14:41,666
CHEF PARK EUN-YEONG'S
THIS IS KANGNAM STYLE

2021
01:14:41,733 --> 01:14:44,233
Please pour the sauce on the noodles

2022
01:14:44,300 --> 01:14:45,300
like scorched rice soup.

2023
01:14:45,633 --> 01:14:48,100
PLEASE EXCUSE THE CHOW MEIN

2024
01:14:48,166 --> 01:14:50,466
-It looks good.
-It looks so good.

2025
01:14:50,533 --> 01:14:52,700
-It's still standing.
-It is.

2026
01:14:52,933 --> 01:14:55,133
AN INSANE VISUAL

2027
01:14:55,200 --> 01:14:57,000
It already looks cool.

2028
01:14:57,066 --> 01:14:58,633
It doesn't collapse.

2029
01:14:58,700 --> 01:15:00,566
-I'll be like Nam-no.
-The chopsticks are in the air.

2030
01:15:01,666 --> 01:15:03,833
These chopsticks
are just for decoration, right?

2031
01:15:03,900 --> 01:15:05,833
Lift it and see if you can lift it.

2032
01:15:05,900 --> 01:15:08,066
TA-DA

2033
01:15:08,133 --> 01:15:09,200
It hardened nicely.

2034
01:15:09,266 --> 01:15:12,966
Sang-hwa is going to hate
this moment right now.

2035
01:15:13,033 --> 01:15:14,266
This moment.

2036
01:15:14,566 --> 01:15:17,933
HONEY, ARE YOU WATCHING THIS?

2037
01:15:18,200 --> 01:15:19,466
VERY PLEASED

2038
01:15:19,533 --> 01:15:21,566
Are you watching this, Sang-hwa?

2039
01:15:21,633 --> 01:15:22,966
I'M GOING TO EAT THIS

2040
01:15:23,033 --> 01:15:24,066
WAIT, ARE YOU MAD?

2041
01:15:25,466 --> 01:15:26,600
WILL YOU GET MAD AT ME?

2042
01:15:26,666 --> 01:15:29,900
-That's the thumbnail.
-The thumbnail.

2043
01:15:29,966 --> 01:15:31,500
-She'd hate it.
-She must be frustrated.

2044
01:15:31,566 --> 01:15:33,033
She'll get really mad.

2045
01:15:33,100 --> 01:15:34,233
Can I just cut it and eat it?

2046
01:15:34,300 --> 01:15:36,533
If you finish that,
you'll get some fat in your liver.

2047
01:15:37,200 --> 01:15:38,666
You can eat it all.

2048
01:15:38,733 --> 01:15:41,066
-It seems like…
-But it's soft.

2049
01:15:41,133 --> 01:15:43,300
-It looks soft.
-It's moist on the inside.

2050
01:15:43,366 --> 01:15:45,500
-It'll come undone soon.
-Yes.

2051
01:15:45,566 --> 01:15:48,466
It'll get moist soon.
What will Sang-hwa say?

2052
01:15:48,533 --> 01:15:50,366
GOING IN

2053
01:15:50,433 --> 01:15:52,666
Something sounds crispy.

2054
01:15:52,733 --> 01:15:53,733
CHUCKLE

2055
01:15:55,933 --> 01:15:59,466
This is a dish that Kangnam has to like.

2056
01:16:00,666 --> 01:16:03,400
-Why?
-Why do you seem so restless?

2057
01:16:03,466 --> 01:16:04,433
I mean,

2058
01:16:04,500 --> 01:16:08,433
-this is insane. It's so good.
-It's so good!

2059
01:16:08,500 --> 01:16:10,100
Toward the end of the bite,

2060
01:16:10,166 --> 01:16:11,866
-something spicy hits me.
-Yes.

2061
01:16:11,933 --> 01:16:13,133
Is that Poong?

2062
01:16:13,200 --> 01:16:15,900
-Yes, I splashed his oil on top.
-I love it!

2063
01:16:15,966 --> 01:16:17,700
I really love it.

2064
01:16:17,766 --> 01:16:19,233
I mean, how can I put this?

2065
01:16:19,300 --> 01:16:22,900
Toward the end of that bite,
it comes in and hits you.

2066
01:16:22,966 --> 01:16:24,466
-You're amazing.
-He makes

2067
01:16:24,533 --> 01:16:26,233
-great chili oil.
-He's good.

2068
01:16:26,300 --> 01:16:28,200
It doesn't punch you too hard, though.

2069
01:16:28,266 --> 01:16:30,333
It jabs you just perfectly.

2070
01:16:30,400 --> 01:16:32,066
It's state-of-the-art.

2071
01:16:32,133 --> 01:16:34,700
-The chili oil played a part.
-But too much would've been bad.

2072
01:16:34,766 --> 01:16:37,433
A chef must be able to tell
if an ingredient is good or not,

2073
01:16:37,500 --> 01:16:38,500
and it was clearly

2074
01:16:38,566 --> 01:16:39,700
really good chili oil.

2075
01:16:39,766 --> 01:16:42,600
-"Really good"?
-You could tell immediately?

2076
01:16:42,666 --> 01:16:43,800
I'm so angry.

2077
01:16:44,933 --> 01:16:46,633
This is so good.

2078
01:16:46,700 --> 01:16:48,366
-It's so good?
-Yes.

2079
01:16:48,433 --> 01:16:51,033
The noodles
are the same color as his hair.

2080
01:16:51,100 --> 01:16:54,333
I keep hearing the crunchy sound
every time he bites it.

2081
01:16:54,400 --> 01:16:55,400
-Hey.
-Yes?

2082
01:16:55,466 --> 01:16:57,166
It keeps changing with each bite.

2083
01:16:57,233 --> 01:16:58,700
-The texture?
-The texture of the noodles.

2084
01:16:58,766 --> 01:17:01,666
-As time goes by?
-It becomes softer and softer.

2085
01:17:01,733 --> 01:17:02,733
It keeps me interested.

2086
01:17:03,833 --> 01:17:05,733
-You don't have to use a knife now.
-Not boring at all.

2087
01:17:06,500 --> 01:17:07,800
What about this part?

2088
01:17:07,866 --> 01:17:11,433
-It'll fall down after about an hour.
-After an hour?

2089
01:17:11,500 --> 01:17:13,766
-An hour?
-He has to eat for an hour?

2090
01:17:13,833 --> 01:17:15,066
-An hour?
-To eat that?

2091
01:17:15,133 --> 01:17:16,566
You have to eat it slowly.

2092
01:17:16,633 --> 01:17:19,066
-So Sang-hwa will be mad for an hour.
-For an hour.

2093
01:17:19,133 --> 01:17:20,966
He can pull them apart now.

2094
01:17:21,566 --> 01:17:22,466
TWO BITES FOR KANGNAM

2095
01:17:23,033 --> 01:17:25,833
Mushroom. Shiitake. Squid.

2096
01:17:25,900 --> 01:17:27,133
Are these squid and shrimp

2097
01:17:27,200 --> 01:17:28,966
in the sauce?

2098
01:17:29,033 --> 01:17:32,666
-The seafood goes well with the sauce.
-The seafood.

2099
01:17:32,933 --> 01:17:34,666
ANOTHER BITE

2100
01:17:35,366 --> 01:17:36,966
Is this a Chinese dish?

2101
01:17:37,033 --> 01:17:40,066
I tried to make the sauce
like that of a scorched rice soup.

2102
01:17:40,133 --> 01:17:42,500
-I got the inspiration there.
-That's it.

2103
01:17:42,566 --> 01:17:46,666
There's a similar, less spicy
Japanese dish called <i>sara</i> udon.

2104
01:17:46,733 --> 01:17:49,333
-It's so good. It's just my taste.
-I'm sure.

2105
01:17:49,400 --> 01:17:51,733
It's like scorched rice soup
if it weren't noodles.

2106
01:17:51,800 --> 01:17:52,733
This is crazy!

2107
01:17:52,800 --> 01:17:54,233
-It's crazy!
-It is?

2108
01:17:54,300 --> 01:17:56,266
-It's insane!
-Look at the camera.

2109
01:17:56,333 --> 01:17:58,700
Sang-hwa is watching, so look.

2110
01:17:58,766 --> 01:18:00,100
HELLO, HONEY

2111
01:18:00,700 --> 01:18:02,733
ARE YOU WATCHING ME?

2112
01:18:02,800 --> 01:18:04,966
-It's like he has no tomorrow.
-He's different.

2113
01:18:05,033 --> 01:18:06,733
If you get beat, you get beat,
so eat for now.

2114
01:18:06,800 --> 01:18:07,966
To be honest,

2115
01:18:08,033 --> 01:18:09,166
one downside is that

2116
01:18:09,233 --> 01:18:11,500
it would've been perfect
along with some beer.

2117
01:18:11,566 --> 01:18:13,233
It calls for beer.

2118
01:18:13,300 --> 01:18:16,466
The greasiness would go so well with beer.

2119
01:18:16,533 --> 01:18:19,833
-But he didn't have beer. What a shame.
-No.

2120
01:18:19,900 --> 01:18:22,866
-It's state-of-the-art.
-State-of-the-art.

2121
01:18:22,933 --> 01:18:25,533
Next, Webtoon Artist Poong's dish.

2122
01:18:26,100 --> 01:18:27,766
<i>Where Poong Goes, Kangnam Follows.</i>

2123
01:18:27,833 --> 01:18:29,333
A REINTERPRETATION
OF AUTHENTIC(?) JJAMJJA-MYEON

2124
01:18:30,433 --> 01:18:33,900
CHOCOLATE SAUCE AS JJAJANG

2125
01:18:35,600 --> 01:18:38,966
AND JJAMPPONG
MADE WITH GREEN ONION KIMCHI

2126
01:18:39,866 --> 01:18:43,866
WEBTOON ARTIST KIM POONG'S
WHERE POONG GOES, KANGNAM FOLLOWS

2127
01:18:43,933 --> 01:18:45,133
<i>Jjamppong</i> first, right?

2128
01:18:45,200 --> 01:18:46,033
Yes, that's right.

2129
01:18:46,100 --> 01:18:47,833
That <i>jjajangmyeon</i>

2130
01:18:47,900 --> 01:18:50,400
looks like an extraterrestrial life.

2131
01:18:50,466 --> 01:18:51,800
-But it smells…
-What's it like?

2132
01:18:51,866 --> 01:18:54,266
I can only smell the chocolate.

2133
01:18:54,333 --> 01:18:57,366
-It's way too strong.
-The chocolate is too strong.

2134
01:18:57,433 --> 01:18:59,133
I can't tell what it smells like.

2135
01:18:59,200 --> 01:19:01,066
I hope the noodles were cooked well.

2136
01:19:01,133 --> 01:19:03,033
-The noodles are important.
-It's important.

2137
01:19:03,100 --> 01:19:04,633
Those look so delicious.

2138
01:19:04,700 --> 01:19:07,566
Japan also has noodles like this one.

2139
01:19:07,633 --> 01:19:11,100
Chef Hyun-suk said
he shouldn't have cooked it in the soup.

2140
01:19:11,800 --> 01:19:13,600
He threw in the uncooked noodles.

2141
01:19:15,433 --> 01:19:16,266
A SIP OF SOUP

2142
01:19:16,333 --> 01:19:18,200
It must've been ages
since he has had <i>jjamppong</i>.

2143
01:19:18,266 --> 01:19:19,300
-I'm sure.
-Yes.

2144
01:19:21,233 --> 01:19:24,400
She didn't even let him order
delivery food.

2145
01:19:24,466 --> 01:19:26,600
He might choke up.

2146
01:19:26,666 --> 01:19:29,766
His managers snitched on him too.

2147
01:19:29,833 --> 01:19:32,133
His eyes have gone crazy already.

2148
01:19:32,666 --> 01:19:34,000
LOSING HIMSELF BEFORE JJAMPPONG

2149
01:19:34,066 --> 01:19:35,166
He's out of it.

2150
01:19:35,233 --> 01:19:36,533
He must love <i>jjamppong</i>.

2151
01:19:36,600 --> 01:19:37,600
Damn, man.

2152
01:19:39,833 --> 01:19:42,100
What was that? "Damn"?

2153
01:19:42,166 --> 01:19:43,700
-Kangnam!
-Hey.

2154
01:19:44,300 --> 01:19:47,233
What's it like? Is it good? The <i>jjamppong</i>.

2155
01:19:47,300 --> 01:19:49,033
He's the best.

2156
01:19:49,100 --> 01:19:50,733
The best?

2157
01:19:50,800 --> 01:19:52,933
-Number one.
-Number one.

2158
01:19:53,000 --> 01:19:53,866
Number one.

2159
01:19:53,933 --> 01:19:56,200
My friend, Poong,

2160
01:19:56,266 --> 01:19:58,433
is so good at making these things.

2161
01:19:58,500 --> 01:20:00,266
-Those things?
-Those things?

2162
01:20:00,333 --> 01:20:02,200
-Those things?
-These, you know,

2163
01:20:02,766 --> 01:20:05,766
dishes that are bad for you.
He's good at making these.

2164
01:20:05,833 --> 01:20:06,700
He can't help it.

2165
01:20:06,766 --> 01:20:08,066
-Harmful food.
-Seriously,

2166
01:20:08,133 --> 01:20:09,966
I think you're a genius.

2167
01:20:10,033 --> 01:20:11,900
The green onion is really good too.

2168
01:20:11,966 --> 01:20:15,600
You said it was between kimchi<i>-jjigae</i>
and <i>jjamppong</i>.

2169
01:20:15,666 --> 01:20:16,500
A SIP OF SOUP

2170
01:20:16,900 --> 01:20:17,766
It must be new.

2171
01:20:17,833 --> 01:20:19,966
It's not the <i>jjamppong </i>we know.

2172
01:20:20,033 --> 01:20:21,566
It turned into another dish.

2173
01:20:21,633 --> 01:20:23,466
I think it's the green onion kimchi.

2174
01:20:23,533 --> 01:20:25,333
It's been fermented already,

2175
01:20:25,400 --> 01:20:28,033
<i>so it has a distinct flavor</i>
<i>even after it was washed.</i>

2176
01:20:28,100 --> 01:20:30,266
Green onion kimchi has some sourness,

2177
01:20:30,333 --> 01:20:32,100
so when you get sick of <i>jjamppong,</i>

2178
01:20:32,166 --> 01:20:34,433
the kimchi can refresh you all over again.

2179
01:20:34,500 --> 01:20:35,566
He enjoys it so much.

2180
01:20:35,633 --> 01:20:37,366
This calls for soju.

2181
01:20:38,466 --> 01:20:39,866
Beer with Eun-yeong's dish.

2182
01:20:39,933 --> 01:20:40,766
Soju with this one.

2183
01:20:40,833 --> 01:20:44,666
-Sang-hwa will be thrilled about this.
-Sure.

2184
01:20:44,733 --> 01:20:45,833
The noodles too.

2185
01:20:45,900 --> 01:20:47,300
He enjoys it so much.

2186
01:20:47,366 --> 01:20:48,600
CONTINUES TO SLURP

2187
01:20:48,666 --> 01:20:49,700
The soup is insane.

2188
01:20:50,666 --> 01:20:53,433
Why don't you move on
and try the chocolate <i>jjajangmyeon?</i>

2189
01:20:53,500 --> 01:20:54,633
Do I have to?

2190
01:20:54,700 --> 01:20:56,566
You can go there, then come back.

2191
01:20:56,633 --> 01:20:58,866
-Chocolate <i>jjajangmyeon.</i>
-Mix it well.

2192
01:20:58,933 --> 01:21:02,133
-Mix it? Mix it.
-Yes, mix it well.

2193
01:21:02,200 --> 01:21:04,266
It's softer than I thought.

2194
01:21:05,500 --> 01:21:07,233
Chocolate <i>jjajangmyeon</i>.

2195
01:21:07,300 --> 01:21:09,300
A BITE

2196
01:21:11,666 --> 01:21:12,666
GRUNT

2197
01:21:12,733 --> 01:21:14,100
CHUCKLE

2198
01:21:17,166 --> 01:21:19,066
What's wrong?

2199
01:21:19,133 --> 01:21:20,733
I guess that's not so good.

2200
01:21:20,800 --> 01:21:22,433
-Is it bad?
-It's not good, right?

2201
01:21:23,566 --> 01:21:25,100
It's iffy.

2202
01:21:25,166 --> 01:21:27,366
Even though he's a friend.
You can go back to <i>jjamppong</i>.

2203
01:21:27,433 --> 01:21:29,566
-The <i>jjamppong</i> is good.
-Let's go back.

2204
01:21:29,633 --> 01:21:30,866
The <i>jjamppong</i> is better.

2205
01:21:30,933 --> 01:21:32,166
He might be staging that too.

2206
01:21:32,233 --> 01:21:33,433
-My gosh.
-It's even better, yes?

2207
01:21:33,500 --> 01:21:34,700
Doesn't it taste even better now?

2208
01:21:34,766 --> 01:21:35,900
I had to eat this one first.

2209
01:21:36,333 --> 01:21:37,366
CHOCOLATE MADE JJAMPPONG BETTER

2210
01:21:37,433 --> 01:21:39,333
Why is that? It's shocking.

2211
01:21:39,400 --> 01:21:41,633
-It just made this a lot better.
-Even better?

2212
01:21:41,700 --> 01:21:43,966
-Because you had something sweet.
-Yes, it was a surprise.

2213
01:21:44,033 --> 01:21:46,333
It changed the flavor. It's stronger.

2214
01:21:46,400 --> 01:21:49,300
-A bite of that.
-To eat <i>jjamppong</i>. Yes.

2215
01:21:49,366 --> 01:21:50,733
EVEN BETTER

2216
01:21:50,800 --> 01:21:52,100
It's even better.

2217
01:21:52,166 --> 01:21:54,233
-I see.
-I don't think I can choose.

2218
01:21:54,300 --> 01:21:55,433
We'll give you some time.

2219
01:21:56,333 --> 01:21:58,200
-My wife would also…
-Hate this?

2220
01:21:58,266 --> 01:21:59,933
Yes, she might hate it.

2221
01:22:00,000 --> 01:22:02,100
-A dish both Yuna and Sang-hwa hate.
-Both.

2222
01:22:02,166 --> 01:22:04,100
-Please try it, Woo-rim.
-Okay.

2223
01:22:04,166 --> 01:22:07,166
-Thank you.
-First, Chef Eun-yeong's Kangnam Style.

2224
01:22:07,233 --> 01:22:09,666
-I wonder what it's like.
-I'm curious.

2225
01:22:10,433 --> 01:22:12,000
ALSO YUM

2226
01:22:14,133 --> 01:22:15,933
It's like scorched rice soup.

2227
01:22:16,000 --> 01:22:18,900
-It also tastes like <i>ulmyeon.</i>
<i>-Ulmyeon</i>, thick seafood noodles.

2228
01:22:18,966 --> 01:22:20,433
It's a bar snack.

2229
01:22:20,500 --> 01:22:21,866
-It is.
-It calls for beer.

2230
01:22:21,933 --> 01:22:24,200
It's a shame to eat this without a drink.

2231
01:22:24,266 --> 01:22:27,266
It would've been boring
without Poong's chili oil.

2232
01:22:27,333 --> 01:22:29,166
Yes, it was an important component.

2233
01:22:29,233 --> 01:22:31,533
Just as Kangnam had mentioned,

2234
01:22:31,600 --> 01:22:33,833
there's a Japanese dish
similar to this one.

2235
01:22:33,900 --> 01:22:34,933
That's already good,

2236
01:22:35,000 --> 01:22:36,933
but this chili oil plays a big part.

2237
01:22:37,000 --> 01:22:39,533
-Yes.
-It brings out the umami.

2238
01:22:39,600 --> 01:22:42,400
Poong, you made great chili oil

2239
01:22:42,466 --> 01:22:44,733
and ended up helping Eun-yeong.

2240
01:22:44,800 --> 01:22:47,533
Next, Poong's dish.

2241
01:22:47,600 --> 01:22:50,700
Where Poong Goes, Kangnam Follows.

2242
01:22:52,633 --> 01:22:55,300
Wow. How did he create this flavor?

2243
01:22:55,366 --> 01:22:58,633
This one really needs soju.

2244
01:22:58,700 --> 01:22:59,900
It tastes like that thing.

2245
01:23:01,766 --> 01:23:04,300
Green onion kimchi plays a big part.

2246
01:23:05,433 --> 01:23:08,733
I think it tastes
a bit like kimchi<i>-jjigae.</i>

2247
01:23:08,800 --> 01:23:11,233
It's also like moray eel soup.

2248
01:23:11,300 --> 01:23:13,733
Poong is definitely good

2249
01:23:13,800 --> 01:23:16,033
-at making these things.
-"These things."

2250
01:23:16,100 --> 01:23:17,866
I like this one.

2251
01:23:17,933 --> 01:23:19,400
I have a sweet tooth.

2252
01:23:19,466 --> 01:23:21,966
When you eat an ice cream cone,

2253
01:23:22,033 --> 01:23:25,000
-there are chocolate toppings on top.
-Yes.

2254
01:23:25,066 --> 01:23:27,566
It's like when the ice cream melts a bit,
making the chocolate soggy,

2255
01:23:27,633 --> 01:23:30,533
-but it's still good, so you bite into it.
-You're right.

2256
01:23:30,600 --> 01:23:33,166
It's like putting <i>jjamppong</i>
on top of the ice cream cone.

2257
01:23:33,466 --> 01:23:35,033
JONG-WON, YOU!

2258
01:23:35,700 --> 01:23:36,533
The sauce is good,

2259
01:23:36,600 --> 01:23:38,466
but he had to fry the noodles in a hurry,

2260
01:23:38,533 --> 01:23:41,200
so it's a shame
that it's not crunchy on the inside.

2261
01:23:41,766 --> 01:23:43,900
It could've turned out better
if he had more time.

2262
01:23:43,966 --> 01:23:45,066
Chef Sam?

2263
01:23:45,633 --> 01:23:46,733
Oh, me?

2264
01:23:46,800 --> 01:23:47,966
It's so good.

2265
01:23:48,033 --> 01:23:50,333
-Is it?
-I got a thinner piece

2266
01:23:50,400 --> 01:23:53,133
for the chocolate <i>jjajangmyeon</i>,

2267
01:23:53,200 --> 01:23:55,800
so it was very delicious.
It was a surprise.

2268
01:23:55,866 --> 01:23:59,433
-You now have to make a choice.
-This is hard.

2269
01:23:59,500 --> 01:24:01,200
I had a delicious meal today.

2270
01:24:01,266 --> 01:24:02,533
She'd hate both.

2271
01:24:02,600 --> 01:24:04,266
Yes, she would.

2272
01:24:04,333 --> 01:24:06,966
But which one will she make sure

2273
01:24:07,033 --> 01:24:09,300
-she files a formal complaint against?
-What she dreads.

2274
01:24:09,366 --> 01:24:11,466
"Why did you feed my husband this?"

2275
01:24:11,533 --> 01:24:13,800
<i>Press one for Park Eun-yeong</i>

2276
01:24:13,866 --> 01:24:15,366
<i>and two for Kim Poong.</i>

2277
01:24:15,966 --> 01:24:17,066
Oh, gosh.

2278
01:24:17,133 --> 01:24:18,633
Make your decision

2279
01:24:18,700 --> 01:24:20,400
and push a button.

2280
01:24:21,333 --> 01:24:23,533
A dish that'll give Sang-hwa a headache.

2281
01:24:23,600 --> 01:24:25,300
A dish that'll make her faint.

2282
01:24:25,366 --> 01:24:26,400
-Did you pick one?
-Yes.

2283
01:24:26,466 --> 01:24:27,766
He has decided.

2284
01:24:27,833 --> 01:24:29,466
WHO DID KANGNAM CHOOSE?

2285
01:24:30,033 --> 01:24:31,000
I'm sorry.

2286
01:24:31,066 --> 01:24:33,466
Let's find out the result!

2287
01:24:33,533 --> 01:24:34,933
Show us!

2288
01:24:35,000 --> 01:24:37,333
A Dish Lee Sang-hwa Would Hate.

2289
01:24:37,933 --> 01:24:41,200
Eun-yeong has won
all five rounds against Poong.

2290
01:24:41,266 --> 01:24:43,866
She has been winning overwhelmingly.

2291
01:24:43,933 --> 01:24:46,666
Will Eun-yeong win again today?

2292
01:24:46,733 --> 01:24:51,300
Or will Poong seize
his first victory against her?

2293
01:24:51,366 --> 01:24:53,100
Who will Kangnam choose?

2294
01:24:53,166 --> 01:24:56,333
Which one will Sang-hwa hate more?

2295
01:24:56,400 --> 01:24:59,133
Who did Kangnam choose?

2296
01:24:59,200 --> 01:25:01,400
Who did Kangnam choose?

2297
01:25:02,066 --> 01:25:03,033
What's the result?

2298
01:25:03,100 --> 01:25:05,166
PARK EUN-YEONG WINS

2299
01:25:05,533 --> 01:25:06,466
THIS IS KANGNAM STYLE WINS

2300
01:25:06,533 --> 01:25:08,100
It was Park Eun-yeong!

2301
01:25:08,166 --> 01:25:09,433
It was your chili oil.

2302
01:25:09,500 --> 01:25:11,633
Eun-yeong is strong against Poong.

2303
01:25:11,700 --> 01:25:14,000
-She won all six rounds.
-All six rounds.

2304
01:25:14,066 --> 01:25:15,533
All six rounds?

2305
01:25:15,600 --> 01:25:18,166
I loved both dishes,

2306
01:25:18,233 --> 01:25:21,200
and this soup
was perfect for my taste too.

2307
01:25:21,266 --> 01:25:25,100
But they had to make
A Dish Lee Sang-hwa Would Hate,

2308
01:25:25,766 --> 01:25:29,000
and I thought she would hate it the most
if I took a picture with this.

2309
01:25:29,066 --> 01:25:30,666
Also, you took <i>ramyeon</i> noodles,

2310
01:25:30,733 --> 01:25:33,466
boiled them, and deep-fried them again.

2311
01:25:34,033 --> 01:25:36,833
-She'll hate that so much.
-I see.

2312
01:25:36,900 --> 01:25:38,900
If I had a cup of beer with this,

2313
01:25:38,966 --> 01:25:41,700
she'd give me
the silent treatment for a while.

2314
01:25:41,766 --> 01:25:43,866
When I imagined that,

2315
01:25:43,933 --> 01:25:45,833
I had to choose Chef Eun-yeong's dish.

2316
01:25:45,900 --> 01:25:48,033
Anyway, this thing still looks like this.

2317
01:25:49,433 --> 01:25:52,133
This one's stubborn.

2318
01:25:52,200 --> 01:25:54,266
Chef Eun-yeong has won

2319
01:25:54,333 --> 01:25:56,300
all six rounds against Poong.

2320
01:25:56,366 --> 01:25:57,900
How do you feel?

2321
01:25:57,966 --> 01:26:00,266
First of all, I am very grateful

2322
01:26:00,333 --> 01:26:02,866
that Poong gladly shared his chili oil.

2323
01:26:02,933 --> 01:26:05,700
-"Gladly"?
-He didn't do it gladly.

2324
01:26:05,766 --> 01:26:08,166
Also, I'm very thrilled that Sang-hwa will

2325
01:26:08,233 --> 01:26:10,066
file a complaint against me.

2326
01:26:10,466 --> 01:26:12,700
WE HOPE YOU TWO LIVE HAPPILY EVER AFTER

2327
01:26:12,766 --> 01:26:13,766
I'm scared.

2328
01:26:13,833 --> 01:26:15,400
It must feel unfair, Poong.

2329
01:26:15,466 --> 01:26:17,500
One of these days,

2330
01:26:17,566 --> 01:26:21,400
I'm going to steal
Eun-yeong's finished dish.

2331
01:26:21,466 --> 01:26:23,700
-I'll steal the final product.
-I see.

2332
01:26:23,766 --> 01:26:27,000
-Watch out.
-How far will Eun-yeong evolve?

2333
01:26:27,066 --> 01:26:29,333
I can do anything to win a star.

2334
01:26:30,766 --> 01:26:31,800
That's so cool.

2335
01:26:31,866 --> 01:26:33,666
-"Thanks!"
-All right, then.

2336
01:26:33,733 --> 01:26:36,066
Please put a star on Eun-yeong!

2337
01:26:36,133 --> 01:26:37,966
EUN-YEONG TAKES HER FIFTH STAR

2338
01:26:38,033 --> 01:26:40,933
You won all six times against Poong.
Congratulations!

2339
01:26:41,000 --> 01:26:43,300
-Congratulations.
-She's on a roll!

2340
01:26:43,366 --> 01:26:45,633
COMING UP: PREVIEW FOR SHIN YE-EUN
AND LEE JUN-YOUNG'S EPISODE

2341
01:26:45,866 --> 01:26:47,566
What took you so long?

2342
01:26:47,633 --> 01:26:48,966
I missed you to death.

2343
01:26:49,033 --> 01:26:50,266
That's so scary.

2344
01:26:50,833 --> 01:26:51,666
HEHE

2345
01:26:51,733 --> 01:26:53,200
I missed you to death!

2346
01:26:53,466 --> 01:26:54,433
AN UNEXPECTED CHARM

2347
01:26:54,500 --> 01:26:56,400
Please welcome
Shin Ye-eun and Lee Jun-young!

2348
01:26:56,466 --> 01:26:57,833
You're great at variety shows.

2349
01:26:57,900 --> 01:26:59,133
I was born for it.

2350
01:27:00,366 --> 01:27:02,300
She seems similar to Eun-yeong.

2351
01:27:02,366 --> 01:27:04,366
I was a good dancer.

2352
01:27:04,433 --> 01:27:06,100
-I'm really shy.
-You are?

2353
01:27:06,333 --> 01:27:07,200
THAT'S NOT ALL

2354
01:27:07,266 --> 01:27:08,666
YE-EUN INFECTS EVERYONE

2355
01:27:08,733 --> 01:27:10,400
WITH THE CUTENESS VIRUS

2356
01:27:10,466 --> 01:27:11,400
A SPIKE IN INFECTIONS

2357
01:27:11,466 --> 01:27:12,300
That's awful.

2358
01:27:12,366 --> 01:27:14,466
Actor Lee Jun-young is here with us!

2359
01:27:14,533 --> 01:27:15,366
TAKE THESE

2360
01:27:15,433 --> 01:27:16,266
ARGH!

2361
01:27:16,333 --> 01:27:18,433
EVEN THE INTROVERT GETS INFECTED

2362
01:27:18,666 --> 01:27:20,000
THANKS TO THE VARIETY SHOW GENIUS

2363
01:27:20,233 --> 01:27:21,133
THE EXCITED CHEFS

2364
01:27:21,366 --> 01:27:22,300
BEGIN THEIR 15-MINUTE COOK-OFFS

2365
01:27:22,866 --> 01:27:24,933
MORE FOCUSED ON PERFORMING THAN COOKING

2366
01:27:25,000 --> 01:27:27,266
CAPTIVATING VISUALS

2367
01:27:27,333 --> 01:27:28,466
WOW

2368
01:27:28,533 --> 01:27:31,366
-Whoa. She eats the whole thing.
-Her mouth must be big inside.

2369
01:27:31,433 --> 01:27:33,333
It's a taste that makes you happy.

2370
01:27:41,166 --> 01:27:42,300
What are you saying?

2371
01:27:53,300 --> 01:27:58,066
Subtitle translation by: Eunsook Youn
